6518 // stack trace.
6519 GTEST_API_ extern const char kStackTraceMarker[];
6520 
6521 // A secret type that Google Test users don't know about. It has no
6522 // definition on purpose. Therefore it's impossible to create a
6523 // Secret object, which is what we want.
6524 class Secret;
6525 
6526 // Two overloaded helpers for checking at compile time whether an
6527 // expression is a null pointer literal (i.e. NULL or any 0-valued
6528 // compile-time integral constant). Their return values have
6529 // different sizes, so we can use sizeof() to test which version is
6530 // picked by the compiler. These helpers have no implementations, as
6531 // we only need their signatures.
6532 //
6533 // Given IsNullLiteralHelper(x), the compiler will pick the first
6534 // version if x can be implicitly converted to Secret*, and pick the
6535 // second version otherwise. Since Secret is a secret and incomplete
6536 // type, the only expression a user can write that has type Secret* is
6537 // a null pointer literal. Therefore, we know that x is a null
6538 // pointer literal if and only if the first version is picked by the
6539 // compiler.
6540 char IsNullLiteralHelper(Secret* p);
6541 char (&IsNullLiteralHelper(...))[2]; // NOLINT
6542 
6543 // A compile-time bool constant that is true if and only if x is a
6544 // null pointer literal (i.e. NULL or any 0-valued compile-time
6545 // integral constant).
6546 #ifdef GTEST_ELLIPSIS_NEEDS_POD_
6547 // We lose support for NULL detection where the compiler doesn't like
6548 // passing non-POD classes through ellipsis (...).
6549 #define GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(x) false
6550 #else
6551 #define GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(x) \
6552  (sizeof(::testing::internal::IsNullLiteralHelper(x)) == 1)
6553 #endif // GTEST_ELLIPSIS_NEEDS_POD_
6554 
6555 // Appends the user-supplied message to the Google-Test-generated message.
6556 GTEST_API_ String AppendUserMessage(const String& gtest_msg,
6557  const Message& user_msg);
6558 
6559 // A helper class for creating scoped traces in user programs.
6560 class GTEST_API_ ScopedTrace {
6561  public:
6562  // The c'tor pushes the given source file location and message onto
6563  // a trace stack maintained by Google Test.
6564  ScopedTrace(const char* file, int line, const Message& message);
6565 
6566  // The d'tor pops the info pushed by the c'tor.
6567  //
6568  // Note that the d'tor is not virtual in order to be efficient.
6569  // Don't inherit from ScopedTrace!
6570  ~ScopedTrace();
6571 
6572  private:
6573  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ScopedTrace);
6574 } GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_; // A ScopedTrace object does its job in its
6575  // c'tor and d'tor. Therefore it doesn't
6576  // need to be used otherwise.
6577 
6578 // Converts a streamable value to a String. A NULL pointer is
6579 // converted to "(null)". When the input value is a ::string,
6580 // ::std::string, ::wstring, or ::std::wstring object, each NUL
6581 // character in it is replaced with "\\0".
6582 // Declared here but defined in gtest.h, so that it has access
6583 // to the definition of the Message class, required by the ARM
6584 // compiler.
6585 template <typename T>
6586 String StreamableToString(const T& streamable);
6587 
6588 // Formats a value to be used in a failure message.
6589 
6590 #ifdef GTEST_NEEDS_IS_POINTER_
6591 
6592 // These are needed as the Nokia Symbian and IBM XL C/C++ compilers
6593 // cannot decide between const T& and const T* in a function template.
6594 // These compilers _can_ decide between class template specializations
6595 // for T and T*, so a tr1::type_traits-like is_pointer works, and we
6596 // can overload on that.
6597 
6598 // This overload makes sure that all pointers (including
6599 // those to char or wchar_t) are printed as raw pointers.
6600 template <typename T>
6601 inline String FormatValueForFailureMessage(internal::true_type /*dummy*/,
6602  T* pointer) {
6603  return StreamableToString(static_cast<const void*>(pointer));
6604 }
6605 
6606 template <typename T>
6607 inline String FormatValueForFailureMessage(internal::false_type /*dummy*/,
6608  const T& value) {
6609  return StreamableToString(value);
6610 }
6611 
6612 template <typename T>
6613 inline String FormatForFailureMessage(const T& value) {
6614  return FormatValueForFailureMessage(
6615  typename internal::is_pointer<T>::type(), value);
6616 }
6617 
6618 #else
6619 
6620 // These are needed as the above solution using is_pointer has the
6621 // limitation that T cannot be a type without external linkage, when
6622 // compiled using MSVC.
6623 
6624 template <typename T>
6625 inline String FormatForFailureMessage(const T& value) {
6626  return StreamableToString(value);
6627 }
6628

6699 // This template class represents an IEEE floating-point number
6700 // (either single-precision or double-precision, depending on the
6701 // template parameters).
6702 //
6703 // The purpose of this class is to do more sophisticated number
6704 // comparison. (Due to round-off error, etc, it's very unlikely that
6705 // two floating-points will be equal exactly. Hence a naive
6706 // comparison by the == operation often doesn't work.)
6707 //
6708 // Format of IEEE floating-point:
6709 //
6710 // The most-significant bit being the leftmost, an IEEE
6711 // floating-point looks like
6712 //
6713 // sign_bit exponent_bits fraction_bits
6714 //
6715 // Here, sign_bit is a single bit that designates the sign of the
6716 // number.
6717 //
6718 // For float, there are 8 exponent bits and 23 fraction bits.
6719 //
6720 // For double, there are 11 exponent bits and 52 fraction bits.
6721 //
6722 // More details can be found at
6723 // http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_floating-point_standard.
6724 //
6725 // Template parameter:
6726 //
6727 // RawType: the raw floating-point type (either float or double)
6728 template <typename RawType>
6729 class FloatingPoint {
6730  public:
6731  // Defines the unsigned integer type that has the same size as the
6732  // floating point number.
6733  typedef typename TypeWithSize<sizeof(RawType)>::UInt Bits;
6734 
6735  // Constants.
6736 
6737  // # of bits in a number.
6738  static const size_t kBitCount = 8*sizeof(RawType);
6739 
6740  // # of fraction bits in a number.
6741  static const size_t kFractionBitCount =
6742  std::numeric_limits<RawType>::digits - 1;
6743 
6744  // # of exponent bits in a number.
6745  static const size_t kExponentBitCount = kBitCount - 1 - kFractionBitCount;
6746 
6747  // The mask for the sign bit.
6748  static const Bits kSignBitMask = static_cast<Bits>(1) << (kBitCount - 1);
6749 
6750  // The mask for the fraction bits.
6751  static const Bits kFractionBitMask =
6752  ~static_cast<Bits>(0) >> (kExponentBitCount + 1);
6753 
6754  // The mask for the exponent bits.
6755  static const Bits kExponentBitMask = ~(kSignBitMask | kFractionBitMask);
6756 
6757  // How many ULP's (Units in the Last Place) we want to tolerate when
6758  // comparing two numbers. The larger the value, the more error we
6759  // allow. A 0 value means that two numbers must be exactly the same
6760  // to be considered equal.
6761  //
6762  // The maximum error of a single floating-point operation is 0.5
6763  // units in the last place. On Intel CPU's, all floating-point
6764  // calculations are done with 80-bit precision, while double has 64
6765  // bits. Therefore, 4 should be enough for ordinary use.
6766  //
6767  // See the following article for more details on ULP:
6768  // http://www.cygnus-software.com/papers/comparingfloats/comparingfloats.htm.
6769  static const size_t kMaxUlps = 4;
6770 
6771  // Constructs a FloatingPoint from a raw floating-point number.
6772  //
6773  // On an Intel CPU, passing a non-normalized NAN (Not a Number)
6774  // around may change its bits, although the new value is guaranteed
6775  // to be also a NAN. Therefore, don't expect this constructor to
6776  // preserve the bits in x when x is a NAN.
6777  explicit FloatingPoint(const RawType& x) { u_.value_ = x; }
6778 
6779  // Static methods
6780 
6781  // Reinterprets a bit pattern as a floating-point number.
6782  //
6783  // This function is needed to test the AlmostEquals() method.
6784  static RawType ReinterpretBits(const Bits bits) {
6785  FloatingPoint fp(0);
6786  fp.u_.bits_ = bits;
6787  return fp.u_.value_;
6788  }
6789 
6790  // Returns the floating-point number that represent positive infinity.
6791  static RawType Infinity() {
6792  return ReinterpretBits(kExponentBitMask);
6793  }
6794 
6795  // Non-static methods
6796 
6797  // Returns the bits that represents this number.
6798  const Bits &bits() const { return u_.bits_; }
6799 
6800  // Returns the exponent bits of this number.
6801  Bits exponent_bits() const { return kExponentBitMask & u_.bits_; }
6802 
6803  // Returns the fraction bits of this number.
6804  Bits fraction_bits() const { return kFractionBitMask & u_.bits_; }
6805 
6806  // Returns the sign bit of this number.
6807  Bits sign_bit() const { return kSignBitMask & u_.bits_; }
6808 
6809  // Returns true iff this is NAN (not a number).
6810  bool is_nan() const {
6811  // It's a NAN if the exponent bits are all ones and the fraction
6812  // bits are not entirely zeros.
6813  return (exponent_bits() == kExponentBitMask) && (fraction_bits() != 0);
6814  }
6815 
6816  // Returns true iff this number is at most kMaxUlps ULP's away from
6817  // rhs. In particular, this function:
6818  //
6819  // - returns false if either number is (or both are) NAN.
6820  // - treats really large numbers as almost equal to infinity.
6821  // - thinks +0.0 and -0.0 are 0 DLP's apart.
6822  bool AlmostEquals(const FloatingPoint& rhs) const {
6823  // The IEEE standard says that any comparison operation involving
6824  // a NAN must return false.
6825  if (is_nan() || rhs.is_nan()) return false;
6826 
6827  return DistanceBetweenSignAndMagnitudeNumbers(u_.bits_, rhs.u_.bits_)
6828  <= kMaxUlps;
6829  }
6830 
6831  private:
6832  // The data type used to store the actual floating-point number.
6833  union FloatingPointUnion {
6834  RawType value_; // The raw floating-point number.
6835  Bits bits_; // The bits that represent the number.
6836  };
6837 
6838  // Converts an integer from the sign-and-magnitude representation to
6839  // the biased representation. More precisely, let N be 2 to the
6840  // power of (kBitCount - 1), an integer x is represented by the
6841  // unsigned number x + N.
6842  //
6843  // For instance,
6844  //
6845  // -N + 1 (the most negative number representable using
6846  // sign-and-magnitude) is represented by 1;
6847  // 0 is represented by N; and
6848  // N - 1 (the biggest number representable using
6849  // sign-and-magnitude) is represented by 2N - 1.
6850  //
6851  // Read http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signed_number_representations
6852  // for more details on signed number representations.
6853  static Bits SignAndMagnitudeToBiased(const Bits &sam) {
6854  if (kSignBitMask & sam) {
6855  // sam represents a negative number.
6856  return ~sam + 1;
6857  } else {
6858  // sam represents a positive number.
6859  return kSignBitMask | sam;
6860  }
6861  }
6862 
6863  // Given two numbers in the sign-and-magnitude representation,
6864  // returns the distance between them as an unsigned number.
6865  static Bits DistanceBetweenSignAndMagnitudeNumbers(const Bits &sam1,
6866  const Bits &sam2) {
6867  const Bits biased1 = SignAndMagnitudeToBiased(sam1);
6868  const Bits biased2 = SignAndMagnitudeToBiased(sam2);
6869  return (biased1 >= biased2) ? (biased1 - biased2) : (biased2 - biased1);
6870  }
6871 
6872  FloatingPointUnion u_;
6873 };
6874 
6875 // Typedefs the instances of the FloatingPoint template class that we
6876 // care to use.
6877 typedef FloatingPoint<float> Float;
6878 typedef FloatingPoint<double> Double;
6879 
6880 // In order to catch the mistake of putting tests that use different
6881 // test fixture classes in the same test case, we need to assign
6882 // unique IDs to fixture classes and compare them. The TypeId type is
6883 // used to hold such IDs. The user should treat TypeId as an opaque
6884 // type: the only operation allowed on TypeId values is to compare
6885 // them for equality using the == operator.
6886 typedef const void* TypeId;
6887 
6888 template <typename T>
6889 class TypeIdHelper {
6890  public:
6891  // dummy_ must not have a const type. Otherwise an overly eager
6892  // compiler (e.g. MSVC 7.1 & 8.0) may try to merge
6893  // TypeIdHelper<T>::dummy_ for different Ts as an "optimization".
6894  static bool dummy_;
6895 };
6896 
6897 template <typename T>
6898 bool TypeIdHelper<T>::dummy_ = false;
6899 
6900 // GetTypeId<T>() returns the ID of type T. Different values will be
6901 // returned for different types. Calling the function twice with the
6902 // same type argument is guaranteed to return the same ID.
6903 template <typename T>
6904 TypeId GetTypeId() {
6905  // The compiler is required to allocate a different
6906  // TypeIdHelper<T>::dummy_ variable for each T used to instantiate
6907  // the template. Therefore, the address of dummy_ is guaranteed to
6908  // be unique.
6909  return &(TypeIdHelper<T>::dummy_);
6910 }
6911 
6912 // Returns the type ID of ::testing::Test. Always call this instead
6913 // of GetTypeId< ::testing::Test>() to get the type ID of
6914 // ::testing::Test, as the latter may give the wrong result due to a
6915 // suspected linker bug when compiling Google Test as a Mac OS X
6916 // framework.
6917 GTEST_API_ TypeId GetTestTypeId();

6957 // Formats a source file path and a line number as they would appear
6958 // in a compiler error message.
6959 inline String FormatFileLocation(const char* file, int line) {
6960  const char* const file_name = file == NULL ? "unknown file" : file;
6961  if (line < 0) {
6962  return String::Format("%s:", file_name);
6963  }
6964 #ifdef _MSC_VER
6965  return String::Format("%s(%d):", file_name, line);
6966 #else
6967  return String::Format("%s:%d:", file_name, line);
6968 #endif // _MSC_VER
6969 }

7003 bool SkipPrefix(const char* prefix, const char** pstr);

7007 // State of the definition of a type-parameterized test case.
7008 class GTEST_API_ TypedTestCasePState {
7009  public:
7010  TypedTestCasePState() : registered_(false) {}
7011 
7012  // Adds the given test name to defined_test_names_ and return true
7013  // if the test case hasn't been registered; otherwise aborts the
7014  // program.
7015  bool AddTestName(const char* file, int line, const char* case_name,
7016  const char* test_name) {

7018  fprintf(stderr, "%s Test %s must be defined before "
7019  "REGISTER_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P(%s, ...).\n",
7020  FormatFileLocation(file, line).c_str(), test_name, case_name);

7022  posix::Abort();
7023  }

7025  return true;
7026  }

7030  // aborts the program otherwise.
7031  const char* VerifyRegisteredTestNames(
7032  const char* file, int line, const char* registered_tests);
7033 
7034  private:
7035  bool registered_;
7036  ::std::set<const char*> defined_test_names_;
7037 };

7039 // Skips to the first non-space char after the first comma in 'str';
7040 // returns NULL if no comma is found in 'str'.
7041 inline const char* SkipComma(const char* str) {
7042  const char* comma = strchr(str, ',');
7043  if (comma == NULL) {
7044  return NULL;
7045  }
7046  while (isspace(*(++comma))) {}
7047  return comma;
7048 }
7049 
7050 // Returns the prefix of 'str' before the first comma in it; returns
7051 // the entire string if it contains no comma.
7052 inline String GetPrefixUntilComma(const char* str) {
7053  const char* comma = strchr(str, ',');
7054  return comma == NULL ? String(str) : String(str, comma - str);
7055 }
7056 
7057 // TypeParameterizedTest<Fixture, TestSel, Types>::Register()
7058 // registers a list of type-parameterized tests with Google Test. The
7059 // return value is insignificant - we just need to return something
7060 // such that we can call this function in a namespace scope.
7061 //
7062 // Implementation note: The GTEST_TEMPLATE_ macro declares a template
7063 // template parameter. It's defined in gtest-type-util.h.
7064 template <GTEST_TEMPLATE_ Fixture, class TestSel, typename Types>
7065 class TypeParameterizedTest {
7066  public:
7067  // 'index' is the index of the test in the type list 'Types'
7068  // specified in INSTANTIATE_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P(Prefix, TestCase,
7069  // Types). Valid values for 'index' are [0, N - 1] where N is the
7070  // length of Types.
7071  static bool Register(const char* prefix, const char* case_name,
7072  const char* test_names, int index) {
7073  typedef typename Types::Head Type;
7074  typedef Fixture<Type> FixtureClass;
7075  typedef typename GTEST_BIND_(TestSel, Type) TestClass;
7076 
7077  // First, registers the first type-parameterized test in the type
7078  // list.
7079  MakeAndRegisterTestInfo(
7080  String::Format("%s%s%s/%d", prefix, prefix[0] == '\0' ? "" : "/",
7081  case_name, index).c_str(),
7082  GetPrefixUntilComma(test_names).c_str(),
7083  String::Format("TypeParam = %s", GetTypeName<Type>().c_str()).c_str(),
7084  "",
7085  GetTypeId<FixtureClass>(),
7086  TestClass::SetUpTestCase,
7087  TestClass::TearDownTestCase,
7088  new TestFactoryImpl<TestClass>);
7089 
7090  // Next, recurses (at compile time) with the tail of the type list.
7091  return TypeParameterizedTest<Fixture, TestSel, typename Types::Tail>
7092  ::Register(prefix, case_name, test_names, index + 1);
7093  }
7094 };
7095 
7096 // The base case for the compile time recursion.
7097 template <GTEST_TEMPLATE_ Fixture, class TestSel>
7098 class TypeParameterizedTest<Fixture, TestSel, Types0> {
7099  public:
7100  static bool Register(const char* /*prefix*/, const char* /*case_name*/,
7101  const char* /*test_names*/, int /*index*/) {
7102  return true;
7103  }
7104 };
7105 
7106 // TypeParameterizedTestCase<Fixture, Tests, Types>::Register()
7107 // registers *all combinations* of 'Tests' and 'Types' with Google
7108 // Test. The return value is insignificant - we just need to return
7109 // something such that we can call this function in a namespace scope.
7110 template <GTEST_TEMPLATE_ Fixture, typename Tests, typename Types>
7111 class TypeParameterizedTestCase {
7112  public:
7113  static bool Register(const char* prefix, const char* case_name,
7114  const char* test_names) {
7115  typedef typename Tests::Head Head;
7116 
7117  // First, register the first test in 'Test' for each type in 'Types'.
7118  TypeParameterizedTest<Fixture, Head, Types>::Register(
7119  prefix, case_name, test_names, 0);
7120 
7121  // Next, recurses (at compile time) with the tail of the test list.
7122  return TypeParameterizedTestCase<Fixture, typename Tests::Tail, Types>
7123  ::Register(prefix, case_name, SkipComma(test_names));
7124  }
7125 };
7126 
7127 // The base case for the compile time recursion.
7128 template <GTEST_TEMPLATE_ Fixture, typename Types>
7129 class TypeParameterizedTestCase<Fixture, Templates0, Types> {
7130  public:
7131  static bool Register(const char* /*prefix*/, const char* /*case_name*/,
7132  const char* /*test_names*/) {
7133  return true;
7134  }
7135 };

7139 // Returns the current OS stack trace as a String.
7140 //
7141 // The maximum number of stack frames to be included is specified by
7142 // the gtest_stack_trace_depth flag. The skip_count parameter
7143 // specifies the number of top frames to be skipped, which doesn't
7144 // count against the number of frames to be included.
7145 //
7146 // For example, if Foo() calls Bar(), which in turn calls
7147 // GetCurrentOsStackTraceExceptTop(..., 1), Foo() will be included in
7148 // the trace but Bar() and GetCurrentOsStackTraceExceptTop() won't.
7149 GTEST_API_ String GetCurrentOsStackTraceExceptTop(UnitTest* unit_test,

7161 // A simple Linear Congruential Generator for generating random
7162 // numbers with a uniform distribution. Unlike rand() and srand(), it
7163 // doesn't use global state (and therefore can't interfere with user
7164 // code). Unlike rand_r(), it's portable. An LCG isn't very random,
7165 // but it's good enough for our purposes.
7166 class GTEST_API_ Random {
7167  public:
7168  static const UInt32 kMaxRange = 1u << 31;
7169 
7170  explicit Random(UInt32 seed) : state_(seed) {}
7171 
7172  void Reseed(UInt32 seed) { state_ = seed; }
7173 
7174  // Generates a random number from [0, range). Crashes if 'range' is
7175  // 0 or greater than kMaxRange.
7176  UInt32 Generate(UInt32 range);
7177 
7178  private:
7179  UInt32 state_;
7180  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(Random);
7181 };

7186 #define GTEST_MESSAGE_(message, result_type) \
7187  ::testing::internal::AssertHelper(result_type, __FILE__, __LINE__, message) \
7188  = ::testing::Message()

7190 #define GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_(message) \
7191  return GTEST_MESSAGE_(message, ::testing::TestPartResult::kFatalFailure)
7192 
7193 #define GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_(message) \
7194  GTEST_MESSAGE_(message, ::testing::TestPartResult::kNonFatalFailure)
7195 
7196 #define GTEST_SUCCESS_(message) \
7197  GTEST_MESSAGE_(message, ::testing::TestPartResult::kSuccess)
7198 
7199 // Suppresses MSVC warnings 4072 (unreachable code) for the code following
7200 // statement if it returns or throws (or doesn't return or throw in some
7201 // situations).
7202 #define GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement) \
7203  if (::testing::internal::AlwaysTrue()) { statement; }
7204 
7205 #define GTEST_TEST_THROW_(statement, expected_exception, fail) \
7206  GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
7207  if (const char* gtest_msg = "") { \
7208  bool gtest_caught_expected = false; \
7209  try { \
7210  GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement); \
7211  } \
7212  catch (expected_exception const&) { \
7213  gtest_caught_expected = true; \
7214  } \
7215  catch (...) { \
7216  gtest_msg = "Expected: " #statement " throws an exception of type " \
7217  #expected_exception ".\n Actual: it throws a different " \
7218  "type."; \
7219  goto GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_testthrow_, __LINE__); \
7220  } \
7221  if (!gtest_caught_expected) { \
7222  gtest_msg = "Expected: " #statement " throws an exception of type " \
7223  #expected_exception ".\n Actual: it throws nothing."; \
7224  goto GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_testthrow_, __LINE__); \
7225  } \
7226  } else \
7227  GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_testthrow_, __LINE__): \
7228  fail(gtest_msg)
7229 
7230 #define GTEST_TEST_NO_THROW_(statement, fail) \
7231  GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
7232  if (const char* gtest_msg = "") { \
7233  try { \
7234  GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement); \
7235  } \
7236  catch (...) { \
7237  gtest_msg = "Expected: " #statement " doesn't throw an exception.\n" \
7238  " Actual: it throws."; \
7239  goto GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_testnothrow_, __LINE__); \
7240  } \
7241  } else \
7242  GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_testnothrow_, __LINE__): \
7243  fail(gtest_msg)
7244 
7245 #define GTEST_TEST_ANY_THROW_(statement, fail) \
7246  GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
7247  if (const char* gtest_msg = "") { \
7248  bool gtest_caught_any = false; \
7249  try { \
7250  GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement); \
7251  } \
7252  catch (...) { \
7253  gtest_caught_any = true; \
7254  } \
7255  if (!gtest_caught_any) { \
7256  gtest_msg = "Expected: " #statement " throws an exception.\n" \
7257  " Actual: it doesn't."; \
7258  goto GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_testanythrow_, __LINE__); \
7259  } \
7260  } else \
7261  GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_testanythrow_, __LINE__): \
7262  fail(gtest_msg)
7263 
7264 
7265 // Implements Boolean test assertions such as EXPECT_TRUE. expression can be
7266 // either a boolean expression or an AssertionResult. text is a textual
7267 // represenation of expression as it was passed into the EXPECT_TRUE.
7268 #define GTEST_TEST_BOOLEAN_(expression, text, actual, expected, fail) \
7269  GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
7270  if (const ::testing::AssertionResult gtest_ar_ = \
7271  ::testing::AssertionResult(expression)) \
7272  ; \
7273  else \
7274  fail(::testing::internal::GetBoolAssertionFailureMessage(\
7275  gtest_ar_, text, #actual, #expected).c_str())
7276 
7277 #define GTEST_TEST_NO_FATAL_FAILURE_(statement, fail) \
7278  GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
7279  if (const char* gtest_msg = "") { \
7280  ::testing::internal::HasNewFatalFailureHelper gtest_fatal_failure_checker; \
7281  GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement); \
7282  if (gtest_fatal_failure_checker.has_new_fatal_failure()) { \
7283  gtest_msg = "Expected: " #statement " doesn't generate new fatal " \
7284  "failures in the current thread.\n" \
7285  " Actual: it does."; \
7286  goto GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_testnofatal_, __LINE__); \
7287  } \
7288  } else \
7289  GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_testnofatal_, __LINE__): \
7290  fail(gtest_msg)
7291 
7292 // Expands to the name of the class that implements the given test.
7293 #define GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name) \
7294  test_case_name##_##test_name##_Test
7295 
7296 // Helper macro for defining tests.
7297 #define GTEST_TEST_(test_case_name, test_name, parent_class, parent_id)\
7298 class GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name) : public parent_class {\
7299  public:\
7300  GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name)() {}\
7301  private:\
7302  virtual void TestBody();\
7303  static ::testing::TestInfo* const test_info_;\
7304  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(\
7305  GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name));\
7306 };\
7307 \
7308 ::testing::TestInfo* const GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name)\
7309  ::test_info_ =\
7310  ::testing::internal::MakeAndRegisterTestInfo(\
7311  #test_case_name, #test_name, "", "", \
7312  (parent_id), \
7313  parent_class::SetUpTestCase, \
7314  parent_class::TearDownTestCase, \
7315  new ::testing::internal::TestFactoryImpl<\
7316  GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name)>);\
7317 void GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name)::TestBody()

7412 // DeathTest is a class that hides much of the complexity of the
7413 // GTEST_DEATH_TEST_ macro. It is abstract; its static Create method
7414 // returns a concrete class that depends on the prevailing death test
7415 // style, as defined by the --gtest_death_test_style and/or
7416 // --gtest_internal_run_death_test flags.
7417 
7418 // In describing the results of death tests, these terms are used with
7419 // the corresponding definitions:
7420 //
7421 // exit status: The integer exit information in the format specified
7422 // by wait(2)
7423 // exit code: The integer code passed to exit(3), _exit(2), or
7424 // returned from main()
7425 class GTEST_API_ DeathTest {
7426  public:
7427  // Create returns false if there was an error determining the
7428  // appropriate action to take for the current death test; for example,
7429  // if the gtest_death_test_style flag is set to an invalid value.
7430  // The LastMessage method will return a more detailed message in that
7431  // case. Otherwise, the DeathTest pointer pointed to by the "test"
7432  // argument is set. If the death test should be skipped, the pointer
7433  // is set to NULL; otherwise, it is set to the address of a new concrete
7434  // DeathTest object that controls the execution of the current test.
7435  static bool Create(const char* statement, const RE* regex,
7436  const char* file, int line, DeathTest** test);
7437  DeathTest();
7438  virtual ~DeathTest() { }
7439 
7440  // A helper class that aborts a death test when it's deleted.
7441  class ReturnSentinel {
7442  public:
7443  explicit ReturnSentinel(DeathTest* test) : test_(test) { }
7444  ~ReturnSentinel() { test_->Abort(TEST_ENCOUNTERED_RETURN_STATEMENT); }
7445  private:
7446  DeathTest* const test_;
7447  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ReturnSentinel);
7448  } GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_;
7449 
7450  // An enumeration of possible roles that may be taken when a death
7451  // test is encountered. EXECUTE means that the death test logic should
7452  // be executed immediately. OVERSEE means that the program should prepare
7453  // the appropriate environment for a child process to execute the death
7454  // test, then wait for it to complete.
7455  enum TestRole { OVERSEE_TEST, EXECUTE_TEST };
7456 
7457  // An enumeration of the two reasons that a test might be aborted.
7458  enum AbortReason { TEST_ENCOUNTERED_RETURN_STATEMENT, TEST_DID_NOT_DIE };
7459 
7460  // Assumes one of the above roles.
7461  virtual TestRole AssumeRole() = 0;
7462 
7463  // Waits for the death test to finish and returns its status.
7464  virtual int Wait() = 0;
7465 
7466  // Returns true if the death test passed; that is, the test process
7467  // exited during the test, its exit status matches a user-supplied
7468  // predicate, and its stderr output matches a user-supplied regular
7469  // expression.
7470  // The user-supplied predicate may be a macro expression rather
7471  // than a function pointer or functor, or else Wait and Passed could
7472  // be combined.
7473  virtual bool Passed(bool exit_status_ok) = 0;
7474 
7475  // Signals that the death test did not die as expected.
7476  virtual void Abort(AbortReason reason) = 0;
7477 
7478  // Returns a human-readable outcome message regarding the outcome of
7479  // the last death test.
7480  static const char* LastMessage();
7481 
7482  static void set_last_death_test_message(const String& message);
7483 
7484  private:
7485  // A string containing a description of the outcome of the last death test.
7486  static String last_death_test_message_;
7487 
7488  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(DeathTest);
7489 };
7490 
7491 // Factory interface for death tests. May be mocked out for testing.
7492 class DeathTestFactory {
7493  public:
7494  virtual ~DeathTestFactory() { }
7495  virtual bool Create(const char* statement, const RE* regex,
7496  const char* file, int line, DeathTest** test) = 0;
7497 };
7498 
7499 // A concrete DeathTestFactory implementation for normal use.
7500 class DefaultDeathTestFactory : public DeathTestFactory {
7501  public:
7502  virtual bool Create(const char* statement, const RE* regex,
7503  const char* file, int line, DeathTest** test);
7504 };

7506 // Returns true if exit_status describes a process that was terminated
7507 // by a signal, or exited normally with a nonzero exit code.
7508 GTEST_API_ bool ExitedUnsuccessfully(int exit_status);

7510 // This macro is for implementing ASSERT_DEATH*, EXPECT_DEATH*,
7511 // ASSERT_EXIT*, and EXPECT_EXIT*.
7512 #define GTEST_DEATH_TEST_(statement, predicate, regex, fail) \
7513  GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
7514  if (::testing::internal::AlwaysTrue()) { \
7515  const ::testing::internal::RE& gtest_regex = (regex); \
7516  ::testing::internal::DeathTest* gtest_dt; \
7517  if (!::testing::internal::DeathTest::Create(#statement, &gtest_regex, \
7518  __FILE__, __LINE__, &gtest_dt)) { \
7519  goto GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_, __LINE__); \
7520  } \
7521  if (gtest_dt != NULL) { \
7522  ::testing::internal::scoped_ptr< ::testing::internal::DeathTest> \
7523  gtest_dt_ptr(gtest_dt); \
7524  switch (gtest_dt->AssumeRole()) { \
7525  case ::testing::internal::DeathTest::OVERSEE_TEST: \
7526  if (!gtest_dt->Passed(predicate(gtest_dt->Wait()))) { \
7527  goto GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_, __LINE__); \
7528  } \
7529  break; \
7530  case ::testing::internal::DeathTest::EXECUTE_TEST: { \
7531  ::testing::internal::DeathTest::ReturnSentinel \
7532  gtest_sentinel(gtest_dt); \
7533  GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement); \
7534  gtest_dt->Abort(::testing::internal::DeathTest::TEST_DID_NOT_DIE); \
7535  break; \
7536  } \
7537  } \
7538  } \
7539  } else \
7540  GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_, __LINE__): \
7541  fail(::testing::internal::DeathTest::LastMessage())
7542 // The symbol "fail" here expands to something into which a message
7543 // can be streamed.
7544

7551  int a_line,
7552  int an_index,
7553  int a_write_fd)
7554  : file_(a_file), line_(a_line), index_(an_index),
7555  write_fd_(a_write_fd) {}
7556

7559  posix::Close(write_fd_);
7560  }
7561 
7562  String file() const { return file_; }
7563  int line() const { return line_; }
7564  int index() const { return index_; }
7565  int write_fd() const { return write_fd_; }
7566 
7567  private:
7568  String file_;
7569  int line_;
7570  int index_;
7571  int write_fd_;
7572 
7573  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(InternalRunDeathTestFlag);

7583 // This macro is used for implementing macros such as
7584 // EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED and ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED on systems where
7585 // death tests are not supported. Those macros must compile on such systems
7586 // iff EXPECT_DEATH and ASSERT_DEATH compile with the same parameters on
7587 // systems that support death tests. This allows one to write such a macro
7588 // on a system that does not support death tests and be sure that it will
7589 // compile on a death-test supporting system.
7590 //
7591 // Parameters:
7592 // statement - A statement that a macro such as EXPECT_DEATH would test
7593 // for program termination. This macro has to make sure this
7594 // statement is compiled but not executed, to ensure that
7595 // EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED compiles with a certain
7596 // parameter iff EXPECT_DEATH compiles with it.
7597 // regex - A regex that a macro such as EXPECT_DEATH would use to test
7598 // the output of statement. This parameter has to be
7599 // compiled but not evaluated by this macro, to ensure that
7600 // this macro only accepts expressions that a macro such as
7601 // EXPECT_DEATH would accept.
7602 // terminator - Must be an empty statement for EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED
7603 // and a return statement for ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED.
7604 // This ensures that ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED will not
7605 // compile inside functions where ASSERT_DEATH doesn't
7606 // compile.
7607 //
7608 // The branch that has an always false condition is used to ensure that
7609 // statement and regex are compiled (and thus syntactically correct) but
7610 // never executed. The unreachable code macro protects the terminator
7611 // statement from generating an 'unreachable code' warning in case
7612 // statement unconditionally returns or throws. The Message constructor at
7613 // the end allows the syntax of streaming additional messages into the
7614 // macro, for compilational compatibility with EXPECT_DEATH/ASSERT_DEATH.
7615 #define GTEST_UNSUPPORTED_DEATH_TEST_(statement, regex, terminator) \
7616  GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
7617  if (::testing::internal::AlwaysTrue()) { \
7618  GTEST_LOG_(WARNING) \
7619  << "Death tests are not supported on this platform.\n" \
7620  << "Statement '" #statement "' cannot be verified."; \
7621  } else if (::testing::internal::AlwaysFalse()) { \
7622  ::testing::internal::RE::PartialMatch(".*", (regex)); \
7623  GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement); \
7624  terminator; \
7625  } else \
7626  ::testing::Message()
7627 
7628 #endif // GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
7629 
7630 } // namespace internal
7631 } // namespace testing
7632 
7633 #endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_DEATH_TEST_INTERNAL_H_
7634 
7635 namespace testing {
7636 
7637 // This flag controls the style of death tests. Valid values are "threadsafe",
7638 // meaning that the death test child process will re-execute the test binary
7639 // from the start, running only a single death test, or "fast",
7640 // meaning that the child process will execute the test logic immediately
7641 // after forking.
7642 GTEST_DECLARE_string_(death_test_style);
7643 
7644 #if GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
7645 
7646 // The following macros are useful for writing death tests.
7647 
7648 // Here's what happens when an ASSERT_DEATH* or EXPECT_DEATH* is
7649 // executed:
7650 //
7651 // 1. It generates a warning if there is more than one active
7652 // thread. This is because it's safe to fork() or clone() only
7653 // when there is a single thread.
7654 //
7655 // 2. The parent process clone()s a sub-process and runs the death
7656 // test in it; the sub-process exits with code 0 at the end of the
7657 // death test, if it hasn't exited already.
7658 //
7659 // 3. The parent process waits for the sub-process to terminate.
7660 //
7661 // 4. The parent process checks the exit code and error message of
7662 // the sub-process.
7663 //
7664 // Examples:
7665 //
7666 // ASSERT_DEATH(server.SendMessage(56, "Hello"), "Invalid port number");
7667 // for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
7668 // EXPECT_DEATH(server.ProcessRequest(i),
7669 // "Invalid request .* in ProcessRequest()")
7670 // << "Failed to die on request " << i);
7671 // }
7672 //
7673 // ASSERT_EXIT(server.ExitNow(), ::testing::ExitedWithCode(0), "Exiting");
7674 //
7675 // bool KilledBySIGHUP(int exit_code) {
7676 // return WIFSIGNALED(exit_code) && WTERMSIG(exit_code) == SIGHUP;
7677 // }
7678 //
7679 // ASSERT_EXIT(client.HangUpServer(), KilledBySIGHUP, "Hanging up!");
7680 //
7681 // On the regular expressions used in death tests:
7682 //
7683 // On POSIX-compliant systems (*nix), we use the <regex.h> library,
7684 // which uses the POSIX extended regex syntax.
7685 //
7686 // On other platforms (e.g. Windows), we only support a simple regex
7687 // syntax implemented as part of Google Test. This limited
7688 // implementation should be enough most of the time when writing
7689 // death tests; though it lacks many features you can find in PCRE
7690 // or POSIX extended regex syntax. For example, we don't support
7691 // union ("x|y"), grouping ("(xy)"), brackets ("[xy]"), and
7692 // repetition count ("x{5,7}"), among others.
7693 //
7694 // Below is the syntax that we do support. We chose it to be a
7695 // subset of both PCRE and POSIX extended regex, so it's easy to
7696 // learn wherever you come from. In the following: 'A' denotes a
7697 // literal character, period (.), or a single \\ escape sequence;
7698 // 'x' and 'y' denote regular expressions; 'm' and 'n' are for
7699 // natural numbers.
7700 //
7701 // c matches any literal character c
7702 // \\d matches any decimal digit
7703 // \\D matches any character that's not a decimal digit
7704 // \\f matches \f
7705 // \\n matches \n
7706 // \\r matches \r
7707 // \\s matches any ASCII whitespace, including \n
7708 // \\S matches any character that's not a whitespace
7709 // \\t matches \t
7710 // \\v matches \v
7711 // \\w matches any letter, _, or decimal digit
7712 // \\W matches any character that \\w doesn't match
7713 // \\c matches any literal character c, which must be a punctuation
7714 // . matches any single character except \n
7715 // A? matches 0 or 1 occurrences of A
7716 // A* matches 0 or many occurrences of A
7717 // A+ matches 1 or many occurrences of A
7718 // ^ matches the beginning of a string (not that of each line)
7719 // $ matches the end of a string (not that of each line)
7720 // xy matches x followed by y
7721 //
7722 // If you accidentally use PCRE or POSIX extended regex features
7723 // not implemented by us, you will get a run-time failure. In that
7724 // case, please try to rewrite your regular expression within the
7725 // above syntax.
7726 //
7727 // This implementation is *not* meant to be as highly tuned or robust
7728 // as a compiled regex library, but should perform well enough for a
7729 // death test, which already incurs significant overhead by launching
7730 // a child process.
7731 //
7732 // Known caveats:
7733 //
7734 // A "threadsafe" style death test obtains the path to the test
7735 // program from argv[0] and re-executes it in the sub-process. For
7736 // simplicity, the current implementation doesn't search the PATH
7737 // when launching the sub-process. This means that the user must
7738 // invoke the test program via a path that contains at least one
7739 // path separator (e.g. path/to/foo_test and
7740 // /absolute/path/to/bar_test are fine, but foo_test is not). This
7741 // is rarely a problem as people usually don't put the test binary
7742 // directory in PATH.
7743 //
7744 // TODO(wan@google.com): make thread-safe death tests search the PATH.
7745 
7746 // Asserts that a given statement causes the program to exit, with an
7747 // integer exit status that satisfies predicate, and emitting error output
7748 // that matches regex.
7749 #define ASSERT_EXIT(statement, predicate, regex) \
7750  GTEST_DEATH_TEST_(statement, predicate, regex, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
7751 
7752 // Like ASSERT_EXIT, but continues on to successive tests in the
7753 // test case, if any:
7754 #define EXPECT_EXIT(statement, predicate, regex) \
7755  GTEST_DEATH_TEST_(statement, predicate, regex, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
7756 
7757 // Asserts that a given statement causes the program to exit, either by
7758 // explicitly exiting with a nonzero exit code or being killed by a
7759 // signal, and emitting error output that matches regex.
7760 #define ASSERT_DEATH(statement, regex) \
7761  ASSERT_EXIT(statement, ::testing::internal::ExitedUnsuccessfully, regex)
7762 
7763 // Like ASSERT_DEATH, but continues on to successive tests in the
7764 // test case, if any:
7765 #define EXPECT_DEATH(statement, regex) \
7766  EXPECT_EXIT(statement, ::testing::internal::ExitedUnsuccessfully, regex)
7767

7769 
7770 // Tests that an exit code describes a normal exit with a given exit code.
7771 class GTEST_API_ ExitedWithCode {
7772  public:
7773  explicit ExitedWithCode(int exit_code);
7774  bool operator()(int exit_status) const;
7775  private:
7776  // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
7777  void operator=(const ExitedWithCode& other);
7778 
7779  const int exit_code_;
7780 };

7794 // EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH asserts that the given statements die in debug mode.
7795 // The death testing framework causes this to have interesting semantics,
7796 // since the sideeffects of the call are only visible in opt mode, and not
7797 // in debug mode.
7798 //
7799 // In practice, this can be used to test functions that utilize the
7800 // LOG(DFATAL) macro using the following style:
7801 //
7802 // int DieInDebugOr12(int* sideeffect) {
7803 // if (sideeffect) {
7804 // *sideeffect = 12;
7805 // }
7806 // LOG(DFATAL) << "death";
7807 // return 12;
7808 // }
7809 //
7810 // TEST(TestCase, TestDieOr12WorksInDgbAndOpt) {
7811 // int sideeffect = 0;
7812 // // Only asserts in dbg.
7813 // EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH(DieInDebugOr12(&sideeffect), "death");
7814 //
7815 // #ifdef NDEBUG
7816 // // opt-mode has sideeffect visible.
7817 // EXPECT_EQ(12, sideeffect);
7818 // #else
7819 // // dbg-mode no visible sideeffect.
7820 // EXPECT_EQ(0, sideeffect);
7821 // #endif
7822 // }
7823 //
7824 // This will assert that DieInDebugReturn12InOpt() crashes in debug
7825 // mode, usually due to a DCHECK or LOG(DFATAL), but returns the
7826 // appropriate fallback value (12 in this case) in opt mode. If you
7827 // need to test that a function has appropriate side-effects in opt
7828 // mode, include assertions against the side-effects. A general
7829 // pattern for this is:
7830 //
7831 // EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH({
7832 // // Side-effects here will have an effect after this statement in
7833 // // opt mode, but none in debug mode.
7834 // EXPECT_EQ(12, DieInDebugOr12(&sideeffect));
7835 // }, "death");
7836 //
7837 #ifdef NDEBUG
7838 
7839 #define EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
7840  do { statement; } while (::testing::internal::AlwaysFalse())
7841 
7842 #define ASSERT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
7843  do { statement; } while (::testing::internal::AlwaysFalse())
7844 
7845 #else
7846 
7847 #define EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
7848  EXPECT_DEATH(statement, regex)
7849 
7850 #define ASSERT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
7851  ASSERT_DEATH(statement, regex)
7852 
7853 #endif // NDEBUG for EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH
7854 #endif // GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
7855 
7856 // EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) and
7857 // ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) expand to real death tests if
7858 // death tests are supported; otherwise they just issue a warning. This is
7859 // useful when you are combining death test assertions with normal test
7860 // assertions in one test.
7861 #if GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
7862 #define EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
7863  EXPECT_DEATH(statement, regex)
7864 #define ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
7865  ASSERT_DEATH(statement, regex)
7866 #else
7867 #define EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
7868  GTEST_UNSUPPORTED_DEATH_TEST_(statement, regex, )
7869 #define ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
7870  GTEST_UNSUPPORTED_DEATH_TEST_(statement, regex, return)
7871 #endif
7872 
7873 } // namespace testing
7874 
7875 #endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_DEATH_TEST_H_

7927 namespace testing {

7929 // The Message class works like an ostream repeater.
7930 //
7931 // Typical usage:
7932 //
7933 // 1. You stream a bunch of values to a Message object.
7934 // It will remember the text in a StrStream.
7935 // 2. Then you stream the Message object to an ostream.
7936 // This causes the text in the Message to be streamed
7937 // to the ostream.
7938 //
7939 // For example;
7940 //
7941 // testing::Message foo;
7942 // foo << 1 << " != " << 2;
7943 // std::cout << foo;
7944 //
7945 // will print "1 != 2".
7946 //
7947 // Message is not intended to be inherited from. In particular, its
7948 // destructor is not virtual.
7949 //
7950 // Note that StrStream behaves differently in gcc and in MSVC. You
7951 // can stream a NULL char pointer to it in the former, but not in the
7952 // latter (it causes an access violation if you do). The Message
7953 // class hides this difference by treating a NULL char pointer as
7954 // "(null)".
7955 class GTEST_API_ Message {
7956  private:
7957  // The type of basic IO manipulators (endl, ends, and flush) for
7958  // narrow streams.
7959  typedef std::ostream& (*BasicNarrowIoManip)(std::ostream&);
7960 
7961  public:
7962  // Constructs an empty Message.
7963  // We allocate the StrStream separately because it otherwise each use of
7964  // ASSERT/EXPECT in a procedure adds over 200 bytes to the procedure's
7965  // stack frame leading to huge stack frames in some cases; gcc does not reuse
7966  // the stack space.
7967  Message() : ss_(new internal::StrStream) {
7968  // By default, we want there to be enough precision when printing
7969  // a double to a Message.
7970  *ss_ << std::setprecision(std::numeric_limits<double>::digits10 + 2);
7971  }
7972 
7973  // Copy constructor.
7974  Message(const Message& msg) : ss_(new internal::StrStream) { // NOLINT
7975  *ss_ << msg.GetString();
7976  }
7977 
7978  // Constructs a Message from a C-string.
7979  explicit Message(const char* str) : ss_(new internal::StrStream) {
7980  *ss_ << str;
7981  }
7982 
7983  ~Message() { delete ss_; }
7984 #if GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
7985  // Streams a value (either a pointer or not) to this object.
7986  template <typename T>
7987  inline Message& operator <<(const T& value) {
7988  StreamHelper(typename internal::is_pointer<T>::type(), value);
7989  return *this;
7990  }
7991 #else
7992  // Streams a non-pointer value to this object.
7993  template <typename T>
7994  inline Message& operator <<(const T& val) {
7995  ::GTestStreamToHelper(ss_, val);
7996  return *this;
7997  }
7998 
7999  // Streams a pointer value to this object.
8000  //
8001  // This function is an overload of the previous one. When you
8002  // stream a pointer to a Message, this definition will be used as it
8003  // is more specialized. (The C++ Standard, section
8004  // [temp.func.order].) If you stream a non-pointer, then the
8005  // previous definition will be used.
8006  //
8007  // The reason for this overload is that streaming a NULL pointer to
8008  // ostream is undefined behavior. Depending on the compiler, you
8009  // may get "0", "(nil)", "(null)", or an access violation. To
8010  // ensure consistent result across compilers, we always treat NULL
8011  // as "(null)".
8012  template <typename T>
8013  inline Message& operator <<(T* const& pointer) { // NOLINT
8014  if (pointer == NULL) {
8015  *ss_ << "(null)";
8016  } else {
8017  ::GTestStreamToHelper(ss_, pointer);
8018  }
8019  return *this;
8020  }
8021 #endif // GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
8022 
8023  // Since the basic IO manipulators are overloaded for both narrow
8024  // and wide streams, we have to provide this specialized definition
8025  // of operator <<, even though its body is the same as the
8026  // templatized version above. Without this definition, streaming
8027  // endl or other basic IO manipulators to Message will confuse the
8028  // compiler.
8029  Message& operator <<(BasicNarrowIoManip val) {
8030  *ss_ << val;
8031  return *this;
8032  }
8033 
8034  // Instead of 1/0, we want to see true/false for bool values.
8035  Message& operator <<(bool b) {
8036  return *this << (b ? "true" : "false");
8037  }
8038 
8039  // These two overloads allow streaming a wide C string to a Message
8040  // using the UTF-8 encoding.
8041  Message& operator <<(const wchar_t* wide_c_str) {
8042  return *this << internal::String::ShowWideCString(wide_c_str);
8043  }
8044  Message& operator <<(wchar_t* wide_c_str) {
8045  return *this << internal::String::ShowWideCString(wide_c_str);
8046  }
8047 
8048 #if GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
8049  // Converts the given wide string to a narrow string using the UTF-8
8050  // encoding, and streams the result to this Message object.
8051  Message& operator <<(const ::std::wstring& wstr);
8052 #endif // GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
8053 
8054 #if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
8055  // Converts the given wide string to a narrow string using the UTF-8
8056  // encoding, and streams the result to this Message object.
8057  Message& operator <<(const ::wstring& wstr);
8058 #endif // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
8059 
8060  // Gets the text streamed to this object so far as a String.
8061  // Each '\0' character in the buffer is replaced with "\\0".
8062  //
8063  // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
8064  internal::String GetString() const {
8065  return internal::StrStreamToString(ss_);
8066  }
8067 
8068  private:
8069 #if GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
8070  // These are needed as the Nokia Symbian Compiler cannot decide between
8071  // const T& and const T* in a function template. The Nokia compiler _can_
8072  // decide between class template specializations for T and T*, so a
8073  // tr1::type_traits-like is_pointer works, and we can overload on that.
8074  template <typename T>
8075  inline void StreamHelper(internal::true_type /*dummy*/, T* pointer) {
8076  if (pointer == NULL) {
8077  *ss_ << "(null)";
8078  } else {
8079  ::GTestStreamToHelper(ss_, pointer);
8080  }
8081  }
8082  template <typename T>
8083  inline void StreamHelper(internal::false_type /*dummy*/, const T& value) {
8084  ::GTestStreamToHelper(ss_, value);
8085  }
8086 #endif // GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
8087 
8088  // We'll hold the text streamed to this object here.
8089  internal::StrStream* const ss_;
8090 
8091  // We declare (but don't implement) this to prevent the compiler
8092  // from implementing the assignment operator.
8093  void operator=(const Message&);
8094 };
8095 
8096 // Streams a Message to an ostream.
8097 inline std::ostream& operator <<(std::ostream& os, const Message& sb) {
8098  return os << sb.GetString();
8099 }
8100 
8101 } // namespace testing
8102 
8103 #endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_MESSAGE_H_

8146 // Value-parameterized tests allow you to test your code with different
8147 // parameters without writing multiple copies of the same test.
8148 //
8149 // Here is how you use value-parameterized tests:
8150 
8151 #if 0
8152 
8153 // To write value-parameterized tests, first you should define a fixture
8154 // class. It must be derived from testing::TestWithParam<T>, where T is
8155 // the type of your parameter values. TestWithParam<T> is itself derived
8156 // from testing::Test. T can be any copyable type. If it's a raw pointer,
8157 // you are responsible for managing the lifespan of the pointed values.
8158 
8159 class FooTest : public ::testing::TestWithParam<const char*> {
8160  // You can implement all the usual class fixture members here.
8161 };
8162 
8163 // Then, use the TEST_P macro to define as many parameterized tests
8164 // for this fixture as you want. The _P suffix is for "parameterized"
8165 // or "pattern", whichever you prefer to think.
8166 
8167 TEST_P(FooTest, DoesBlah) {
8168  // Inside a test, access the test parameter with the GetParam() method
8169  // of the TestWithParam<T> class:
8170  EXPECT_TRUE(foo.Blah(GetParam()));
8171  ...
8172 }
8173 
8174 TEST_P(FooTest, HasBlahBlah) {
8175  ...
8176 }
8177 
8178 // Finally, you can use INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P to instantiate the test
8179 // case with any set of parameters you want. Google Test defines a number
8180 // of functions for generating test parameters. They return what we call
8181 // (surprise!) parameter generators. Here is a summary of them, which
8182 // are all in the testing namespace:
8183 //
8184 //
8185 // Range(begin, end [, step]) - Yields values {begin, begin+step,
8186 // begin+step+step, ...}. The values do not
8187 // include end. step defaults to 1.
8188 // Values(v1, v2, ..., vN) - Yields values {v1, v2, ..., vN}.
8189 // ValuesIn(container) - Yields values from a C-style array, an STL
8190 // ValuesIn(begin,end) container, or an iterator range [begin, end).
8191 // Bool() - Yields sequence {false, true}.
8192 // Combine(g1, g2, ..., gN) - Yields all combinations (the Cartesian product
8193 // for the math savvy) of the values generated
8194 // by the N generators.
8195 //
8196 // For more details, see comments at the definitions of these functions below
8197 // in this file.
8198 //
8199 // The following statement will instantiate tests from the FooTest test case
8200 // each with parameter values "meeny", "miny", and "moe".
8201 
8202 INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(InstantiationName,
8203  FooTest,
8204  Values("meeny", "miny", "moe"));
8205 
8206 // To distinguish different instances of the pattern, (yes, you
8207 // can instantiate it more then once) the first argument to the
8208 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P macro is a prefix that will be added to the
8209 // actual test case name. Remember to pick unique prefixes for different
8210 // instantiations. The tests from the instantiation above will have
8211 // these names:
8212 //
8213 // * InstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/0 for "meeny"
8214 // * InstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/1 for "miny"
8215 // * InstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/2 for "moe"
8216 // * InstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/0 for "meeny"
8217 // * InstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/1 for "miny"
8218 // * InstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/2 for "moe"
8219 //
8220 // You can use these names in --gtest_filter.
8221 //
8222 // This statement will instantiate all tests from FooTest again, each
8223 // with parameter values "cat" and "dog":
8224 
8225 const char* pets[] = {"cat", "dog"};
8226 INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(AnotherInstantiationName, FooTest, ValuesIn(pets));
8227 
8228 // The tests from the instantiation above will have these names:
8229 //
8230 // * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/0 for "cat"
8231 // * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/1 for "dog"
8232 // * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/0 for "cat"
8233 // * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/1 for "dog"
8234 //
8235 // Please note that INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P will instantiate all tests
8236 // in the given test case, whether their definitions come before or
8237 // AFTER the INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P statement.
8238 //
8239 // Please also note that generator expressions (including parameters to the
8240 // generators) are evaluated in InitGoogleTest(), after main() has started.
8241 // This allows the user on one hand, to adjust generator parameters in order
8242 // to dynamically determine a set of tests to run and on the other hand,
8243 // give the user a chance to inspect the generated tests with Google Test
8244 // reflection API before RUN_ALL_TESTS() is executed.
8245 //
8246 // You can see samples/sample7_unittest.cc and samples/sample8_unittest.cc
8247 // for more examples.
8248 //
8249 // In the future, we plan to publish the API for defining new parameter
8250 // generators. But for now this interface remains part of the internal
8251 // implementation and is subject to change.
8252

8337 // A "smart" pointer type with reference tracking. Every pointer to a
8338 // particular object is kept on a circular linked list. When the last pointer
8339 // to an object is destroyed or reassigned, the object is deleted.
8340 //
8341 // Used properly, this deletes the object when the last reference goes away.
8342 // There are several caveats:
8343 // - Like all reference counting schemes, cycles lead to leaks.
8344 // - Each smart pointer is actually two pointers (8 bytes instead of 4).
8345 // - Every time a pointer is assigned, the entire list of pointers to that
8346 // object is traversed. This class is therefore NOT SUITABLE when there
8347 // will often be more than two or three pointers to a particular object.
8348 // - References are only tracked as long as linked_ptr<> objects are copied.
8349 // If a linked_ptr<> is converted to a raw pointer and back, BAD THINGS
8350 // will happen (double deletion).
8351 //
8352 // A good use of this class is storing object references in STL containers.
8353 // You can safely put linked_ptr<> in a vector<>.
8354 // Other uses may not be as good.
8355 //
8356 // Note: If you use an incomplete type with linked_ptr<>, the class
8357 // *containing* linked_ptr<> must have a constructor and destructor (even
8358 // if they do nothing!).
8359 //
8360 // Bill Gibbons suggested we use something like this.
8361 //
8362 // Thread Safety:
8363 // Unlike other linked_ptr implementations, in this implementation
8364 // a linked_ptr object is thread-safe in the sense that:
8365 // - it's safe to copy linked_ptr objects concurrently,
8366 // - it's safe to copy *from* a linked_ptr and read its underlying
8367 // raw pointer (e.g. via get()) concurrently, and
8368 // - it's safe to write to two linked_ptrs that point to the same
8369 // shared object concurrently.
8370 // TODO(wan@google.com): rename this to safe_linked_ptr to avoid
8371 // confusion with normal linked_ptr.
8372 
8373 #ifndef GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_LINKED_PTR_H_
8374 #define GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_LINKED_PTR_H_
8375 
8376 #include <stdlib.h>
8377 #include <assert.h>
8378 
8379 
8380 namespace testing {
8381 namespace internal {
8382 
8383 // Protects copying of all linked_ptr objects.
8384 GTEST_API_2 GTEST_DECLARE_STATIC_MUTEX_(g_linked_ptr_mutex);
8385 
8386 // This is used internally by all instances of linked_ptr<>. It needs to be
8387 // a non-template class because different types of linked_ptr<> can refer to
8388 // the same object (linked_ptr<Superclass>(obj) vs linked_ptr<Subclass>(obj)).
8389 // So, it needs to be possible for different types of linked_ptr to participate
8390 // in the same circular linked list, so we need a single class type here.
8391 //
8392 // DO NOT USE THIS CLASS DIRECTLY YOURSELF. Use linked_ptr<T>.
8393 class linked_ptr_internal {
8394  public:
8395  // Create a new circle that includes only this instance.
8396  void join_new() {
8397  next_ = this;
8398  }
8399 
8400  // Many linked_ptr operations may change p.link_ for some linked_ptr
8401  // variable p in the same circle as this object. Therefore we need
8402  // to prevent two such operations from occurring concurrently.
8403  //
8404  // Note that different types of linked_ptr objects can coexist in a
8405  // circle (e.g. linked_ptr<Base>, linked_ptr<Derived1>, and
8406  // linked_ptr<Derived2>). Therefore we must use a single mutex to
8407  // protect all linked_ptr objects. This can create serious
8408  // contention in production code, but is acceptable in a testing
8409  // framework.
8410 
8411  // Join an existing circle.
8412  // L < g_linked_ptr_mutex
8413  void join(linked_ptr_internal const* ptr) {
8414  MutexLock lock(&g_linked_ptr_mutex);
8415 
8416  linked_ptr_internal const* p = ptr;
8417  while (p->next_ != ptr) p = p->next_;
8418  p->next_ = this;
8419  next_ = ptr;
8420  }
8421 
8422  // Leave whatever circle we're part of. Returns true if we were the
8423  // last member of the circle. Once this is done, you can join() another.
8424  // L < g_linked_ptr_mutex
8425  bool depart() {
8426  MutexLock lock(&g_linked_ptr_mutex);
8427 
8428  if (next_ == this) return true;
8429  linked_ptr_internal const* p = next_;
8430  while (p->next_ != this) p = p->next_;
8431  p->next_ = next_;
8432  return false;
8433  }
8434 
8435  private:
8436  mutable linked_ptr_internal const* next_;
8437 };
8438 
8439 template <typename T>
8440 class linked_ptr {
8441  public:
8442  typedef T element_type;
8443 
8444  // Take over ownership of a raw pointer. This should happen as soon as
8445  // possible after the object is created.
8446  explicit linked_ptr(T* ptr = NULL) { capture(ptr); }
8447  ~linked_ptr() { depart(); }
8448 
8449  // Copy an existing linked_ptr<>, adding ourselves to the list of references.
8450  template <typename U> linked_ptr(linked_ptr<U> const& ptr) { copy(&ptr); }
8451  linked_ptr(linked_ptr const& ptr) { // NOLINT
8452  assert(&ptr != this);
8453  copy(&ptr);
8454  }
8455 
8456  // Assignment releases the old value and acquires the new.
8457  template <typename U> linked_ptr& operator=(linked_ptr<U> const& ptr) {
8458  depart();
8459  copy(&ptr);
8460  return *this;
8461  }
8462 
8463  linked_ptr& operator=(linked_ptr const& ptr) {
8464  if (&ptr != this) {
8465  depart();
8466  copy(&ptr);
8467  }
8468  return *this;
8469  }
8470 
8471  // Smart pointer members.
8472  void reset(T* ptr = NULL) {
8473  depart();
8474  capture(ptr);
8475  }
8476  T* get() const { return value_; }
8477  T* operator->() const { return value_; }
8478  T& operator*() const { return *value_; }
8479  // Release ownership of the pointed object and returns it.
8480  // Sole ownership by this linked_ptr object is required.
8481  T* release() {
8482  bool last = link_.depart();
8483  assert(last);
8484  T* v = value_;
8485  value_ = NULL;
8486  return v;
8487  }
8488 
8489  bool operator==(T* p) const { return value_ == p; }
8490  bool operator!=(T* p) const { return value_ != p; }
8491  template <typename U>
8492  bool operator==(linked_ptr<U> const& ptr) const {
8493  return value_ == ptr.get();
8494  }
8495  template <typename U>
8496  bool operator!=(linked_ptr<U> const& ptr) const {
8497  return value_ != ptr.get();
8498  }
8499 
8500  private:
8501  template <typename U>
8502  friend class linked_ptr;
8503 
8504  T* value_;
8505  linked_ptr_internal link_;
8506 
8507  void depart() {
8508  if (link_.depart()) delete value_;
8509  }
8510 
8511  void capture(T* ptr) {
8512  value_ = ptr;
8513  link_.join_new();
8514  }
8515 
8516  template <typename U> void copy(linked_ptr<U> const* ptr) {
8517  value_ = ptr->get();
8518  if (value_)
8519  link_.join(&ptr->link_);
8520  else
8521  link_.join_new();
8522  }
8523 };
8524 
8525 template<typename T> inline
8526 bool operator==(T* ptr, const linked_ptr<T>& x) {
8527  return ptr == x.get();
8528 }
8529 
8530 template<typename T> inline
8531 bool operator!=(T* ptr, const linked_ptr<T>& x) {
8532  return ptr != x.get();
8533 }
8534 
8535 // A function to convert T* into linked_ptr<T>
8536 // Doing e.g. make_linked_ptr(new FooBarBaz<type>(arg)) is a shorter notation
8537 // for linked_ptr<FooBarBaz<type> >(new FooBarBaz<type>(arg))
8538 template <typename T>
8539 linked_ptr<T> make_linked_ptr(T* ptr) {
8540  return linked_ptr<T>(ptr);
8541 }
8542 
8543 } // namespace internal
8544 } // namespace testing

8546 #endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_LINKED_PTR_H_

8553 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
8554 //
8555 // Outputs a message explaining invalid registration of different
8556 // fixture class for the same test case. This may happen when
8557 // TEST_P macro is used to define two tests with the same name
8558 // but in different namespaces.
8559 GTEST_API_ void ReportInvalidTestCaseType(const char* test_case_name,
8560  const char* file, int line);

8562 template <typename> class ParamGeneratorInterface;
8563 template <typename> class ParamGenerator;
8564 
8565 // Interface for iterating over elements provided by an implementation
8566 // of ParamGeneratorInterface<T>.
8567 template <typename T>
8568 class ParamIteratorInterface {
8569  public:
8570  virtual ~ParamIteratorInterface() {}
8571  // A pointer to the base generator instance.
8572  // Used only for the purposes of iterator comparison
8573  // to make sure that two iterators belong to the same generator.
8574  virtual const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* BaseGenerator() const = 0;
8575  // Advances iterator to point to the next element
8576  // provided by the generator. The caller is responsible
8577  // for not calling Advance() on an iterator equal to
8578  // BaseGenerator()->End().
8579  virtual void Advance() = 0;
8580  // Clones the iterator object. Used for implementing copy semantics
8581  // of ParamIterator<T>.
8582  virtual ParamIteratorInterface* Clone() const = 0;
8583  // Dereferences the current iterator and provides (read-only) access
8584  // to the pointed value. It is the caller's responsibility not to call
8585  // Current() on an iterator equal to BaseGenerator()->End().
8586  // Used for implementing ParamGenerator<T>::operator*().
8587  virtual const T* Current() const = 0;
8588  // Determines whether the given iterator and other point to the same
8589  // element in the sequence generated by the generator.
8590  // Used for implementing ParamGenerator<T>::operator==().
8591  virtual bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface& other) const = 0;
8592 };
8593 
8594 // Class iterating over elements provided by an implementation of
8595 // ParamGeneratorInterface<T>. It wraps ParamIteratorInterface<T>
8596 // and implements the const forward iterator concept.
8597 template <typename T>
8598 class ParamIterator {
8599  public:
8600  typedef T value_type;
8601  typedef const T& reference;
8602  typedef ptrdiff_t difference_type;
8603 
8604  // ParamIterator assumes ownership of the impl_ pointer.
8605  ParamIterator(const ParamIterator& other) : impl_(other.impl_->Clone()) {}
8606  ParamIterator& operator=(const ParamIterator& other) {
8607  if (this != &other)
8608  impl_.reset(other.impl_->Clone());
8609  return *this;
8610  }
8611 
8612  const T& operator*() const { return *impl_->Current(); }
8613  const T* operator->() const { return impl_->Current(); }
8614  // Prefix version of operator++.
8615  ParamIterator& operator++() {
8616  impl_->Advance();
8617  return *this;
8618  }
8619  // Postfix version of operator++.
8620  ParamIterator operator++(int /*unused*/) {
8621  ParamIteratorInterface<T>* clone = impl_->Clone();
8622  impl_->Advance();
8623  return ParamIterator(clone);
8624  }
8625  bool operator==(const ParamIterator& other) const {
8626  return impl_.get() == other.impl_.get() || impl_->Equals(*other.impl_);
8627  }
8628  bool operator!=(const ParamIterator& other) const {
8629  return !(*this == other);
8630  }
8631 
8632  private:
8633  friend class ParamGenerator<T>;
8634  explicit ParamIterator(ParamIteratorInterface<T>* impl) : impl_(impl) {}
8635  scoped_ptr<ParamIteratorInterface<T> > impl_;
8636 };
8637 
8638 // ParamGeneratorInterface<T> is the binary interface to access generators
8639 // defined in other translation units.
8640 template <typename T>
8641 class ParamGeneratorInterface {
8642  public:
8643  typedef T ParamType;
8644 
8645  virtual ~ParamGeneratorInterface() {}
8646 
8647  // Generator interface definition
8648  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Begin() const = 0;
8649  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* End() const = 0;
8650 };
8651 
8652 // Wraps ParamGeneratorInterface<T> and provides general generator syntax
8653 // compatible with the STL Container concept.
8654 // This class implements copy initialization semantics and the contained
8655 // ParamGeneratorInterface<T> instance is shared among all copies
8656 // of the original object. This is possible because that instance is immutable.
8657 template<typename T>
8658 class ParamGenerator {
8659  public:
8660  typedef ParamIterator<T> iterator;
8661 
8662  explicit ParamGenerator(ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* impl) : impl_(impl) {}
8663  ParamGenerator(const ParamGenerator& other) : impl_(other.impl_) {}
8664 
8665  ParamGenerator& operator=(const ParamGenerator& other) {
8666  impl_ = other.impl_;
8667  return *this;
8668  }
8669 
8670  iterator begin() const { return iterator(impl_->Begin()); }
8671  iterator end() const { return iterator(impl_->End()); }
8672 
8673  private:
8674  ::testing::internal::linked_ptr<const ParamGeneratorInterface<T> > impl_;
8675 };
8676 
8677 // Generates values from a range of two comparable values. Can be used to
8678 // generate sequences of user-defined types that implement operator+() and
8679 // operator<().
8680 // This class is used in the Range() function.
8681 template <typename T, typename IncrementT>
8682 class RangeGenerator : public ParamGeneratorInterface<T> {
8683  public:
8684  RangeGenerator(T begin, T end, IncrementT step)
8685  : begin_(begin), end_(end),
8686  step_(step), end_index_(CalculateEndIndex(begin, end, step)) {}
8687  virtual ~RangeGenerator() {}
8688 
8689  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Begin() const {
8690  return new Iterator(this, begin_, 0, step_);
8691  }
8692  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* End() const {
8693  return new Iterator(this, end_, end_index_, step_);
8694  }
8695 
8696  private:
8697  class Iterator : public ParamIteratorInterface<T> {
8698  public:
8699  Iterator(const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* base, T value, int index,
8700  IncrementT step)
8701  : base_(base), value_(value), index_(index), step_(step) {}
8702  virtual ~Iterator() {}
8703 
8704  virtual const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* BaseGenerator() const {
8705  return base_;
8706  }
8707  virtual void Advance() {
8708  value_ = value_ + step_;
8709  index_++;
8710  }
8711  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Clone() const {
8712  return new Iterator(*this);
8713  }
8714  virtual const T* Current() const { return &value_; }
8715  virtual bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<T>& other) const {
8716  // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
8717  // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
8718  GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
8719  << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
8720  << "from different generators." << std::endl;
8721  const int other_index =
8722  CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other)->index_;
8723  return index_ == other_index;
8724  }
8725 
8726  private:
8727  Iterator(const Iterator& other)
8728  : ParamIteratorInterface<T>(),
8729  base_(other.base_), value_(other.value_), index_(other.index_),
8730  step_(other.step_) {}
8731 
8732  // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
8733  void operator=(const Iterator& other);
8734 
8735  const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* const base_;
8736  T value_;
8737  int index_;
8738  const IncrementT step_;
8739  }; // class RangeGenerator::Iterator
8740 
8741  static int CalculateEndIndex(const T& begin,
8742  const T& end,
8743  const IncrementT& step) {
8744  int end_index = 0;
8745  for (T i = begin; i < end; i = i + step)
8746  end_index++;
8747  return end_index;
8748  }
8749 
8750  // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
8751  void operator=(const RangeGenerator& other);
8752 
8753  const T begin_;
8754  const T end_;
8755  const IncrementT step_;
8756  // The index for the end() iterator. All the elements in the generated
8757  // sequence are indexed (0-based) to aid iterator comparison.
8758  const int end_index_;
8759 }; // class RangeGenerator
8760 
8761 
8762 // Generates values from a pair of STL-style iterators. Used in the
8763 // ValuesIn() function. The elements are copied from the source range
8764 // since the source can be located on the stack, and the generator
8765 // is likely to persist beyond that stack frame.
8766 template <typename T>
8767 class ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator : public ParamGeneratorInterface<T> {
8768  public:
8769  template <typename ForwardIterator>
8770  ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator(ForwardIterator begin, ForwardIterator end)
8771  : container_(begin, end) {}
8772  virtual ~ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator() {}
8773 
8774  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Begin() const {
8775  return new Iterator(this, container_.begin());
8776  }
8777  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* End() const {
8778  return new Iterator(this, container_.end());
8779  }
8780 
8781  private:
8782  typedef typename ::std::vector<T> ContainerType;
8783 
8784  class Iterator : public ParamIteratorInterface<T> {
8785  public:
8786  Iterator(const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* base,
8787  typename ContainerType::const_iterator iterator)
8788  : base_(base), iterator_(iterator) {}
8789  virtual ~Iterator() {}
8790 
8791  virtual const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* BaseGenerator() const {
8792  return base_;
8793  }
8794  virtual void Advance() {
8795  ++iterator_;
8796  value_.reset();
8797  }
8798  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Clone() const {
8799  return new Iterator(*this);
8800  }
8801  // We need to use cached value referenced by iterator_ because *iterator_
8802  // can return a temporary object (and of type other then T), so just
8803  // having "return &*iterator_;" doesn't work.
8804  // value_ is updated here and not in Advance() because Advance()
8805  // can advance iterator_ beyond the end of the range, and we cannot
8806  // detect that fact. The client code, on the other hand, is
8807  // responsible for not calling Current() on an out-of-range iterator.
8808  virtual const T* Current() const {
8809  if (value_.get() == NULL)
8810  value_.reset(new T(*iterator_));
8811  return value_.get();
8812  }
8813  virtual bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<T>& other) const {
8814  // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
8815  // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
8816  GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
8817  << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
8818  << "from different generators." << std::endl;
8819  return iterator_ ==
8820  CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other)->iterator_;
8821  }
8822 
8823  private:
8824  Iterator(const Iterator& other)
8825  // The explicit constructor call suppresses a false warning
8826  // emitted by gcc when supplied with the -Wextra option.
8827  : ParamIteratorInterface<T>(),
8828  base_(other.base_),
8829  iterator_(other.iterator_) {}
8830 
8831  const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* const base_;
8832  typename ContainerType::const_iterator iterator_;
8833  // A cached value of *iterator_. We keep it here to allow access by
8834  // pointer in the wrapping iterator's operator->().
8835  // value_ needs to be mutable to be accessed in Current().
8836  // Use of scoped_ptr helps manage cached value's lifetime,
8837  // which is bound by the lifespan of the iterator itself.
8838  mutable scoped_ptr<const T> value_;
8839  }; // class ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator::Iterator
8840 
8841  // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
8842  void operator=(const ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator& other);
8843 
8844  const ContainerType container_;
8845 }; // class ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator

8904 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
8905 //
8906 // ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase is a generic interface
8907 // to ParameterizedTestCaseInfo classes. ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase
8908 // accumulates test information provided by TEST_P macro invocations
8909 // and generators provided by INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P macro invocations
8910 // and uses that information to register all resulting test instances
8911 // in RegisterTests method. The ParameterizeTestCaseRegistry class holds
8912 // a collection of pointers to the ParameterizedTestCaseInfo objects
8913 // and calls RegisterTests() on each of them when asked.
8914 class ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase {
8915  public:
8916  virtual ~ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase() {}
8917 
8918  // Base part of test case name for display purposes.
8919  virtual const String& GetTestCaseName() const = 0;
8920  // Test case id to verify identity.
8921  virtual TypeId GetTestCaseTypeId() const = 0;
8922  // UnitTest class invokes this method to register tests in this
8923  // test case right before running them in RUN_ALL_TESTS macro.
8924  // This method should not be called more then once on any single
8925  // instance of a ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase derived class.
8926  virtual void RegisterTests() = 0;
8927 
8928  protected:
8929  ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase() {}
8930 
8931  private:
8932  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase);
8933 };
