8935 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
8936 //
8937 // ParameterizedTestCaseInfo accumulates tests obtained from TEST_P
8938 // macro invocations for a particular test case and generators
8939 // obtained from INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P macro invocations for that
8940 // test case. It registers tests with all values generated by all
8941 // generators when asked.
8942 template <class TestCase>
8943 class ParameterizedTestCaseInfo : public ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase {
8944  public:
8945  // ParamType and GeneratorCreationFunc are private types but are required
8946  // for declarations of public methods AddTestPattern() and
8947  // AddTestCaseInstantiation().
8948  typedef typename TestCase::ParamType ParamType;
8949  // A function that returns an instance of appropriate generator type.
8950  typedef ParamGenerator<ParamType>(GeneratorCreationFunc)();
8951 
8952  explicit ParameterizedTestCaseInfo(const char* name)
8953  : test_case_name_(name) {}
8954 
8955  // Test case base name for display purposes.
8956  virtual const String& GetTestCaseName() const { return test_case_name_; }
8957  // Test case id to verify identity.
8958  virtual TypeId GetTestCaseTypeId() const { return GetTypeId<TestCase>(); }
8959  // TEST_P macro uses AddTestPattern() to record information
8960  // about a single test in a LocalTestInfo structure.
8961  // test_case_name is the base name of the test case (without invocation
8962  // prefix). test_base_name is the name of an individual test without
8963  // parameter index. For the test SequenceA/FooTest.DoBar/1 FooTest is
8964  // test case base name and DoBar is test base name.
8965  void AddTestPattern(const char* test_case_name,
8966  const char* test_base_name,
8967  TestMetaFactoryBase<ParamType>* meta_factory) {
8968  tests_.push_back(linked_ptr<TestInfo>(new TestInfo(test_case_name,
8969  test_base_name,
8970  meta_factory)));
8971  }
8972  // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P macro uses AddGenerator() to record information
8973  // about a generator.
8974  int AddTestCaseInstantiation(const char* instantiation_name,
8975  GeneratorCreationFunc* func,
8976  const char* /* file */,
8977  int /* line */) {
8978  instantiations_.push_back(::std::make_pair(instantiation_name, func));
8979  return 0; // Return value used only to run this method in namespace scope.
8980  }
8981  // UnitTest class invokes this method to register tests in this test case
8982  // test cases right before running tests in RUN_ALL_TESTS macro.
8983  // This method should not be called more then once on any single
8984  // instance of a ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase derived class.
8985  // UnitTest has a guard to prevent from calling this method more then once.
8986  virtual void RegisterTests() {
8987  for (typename TestInfoContainer::iterator test_it = tests_.begin();
8988  test_it != tests_.end(); ++test_it) {
8989  linked_ptr<TestInfo> test_info = *test_it;
8990  for (typename InstantiationContainer::iterator gen_it =
8991  instantiations_.begin(); gen_it != instantiations_.end();
8992  ++gen_it) {
8993  const String& instantiation_name = gen_it->first;
8994  ParamGenerator<ParamType> generator((*gen_it->second)());
8995 
8996  Message test_case_name_stream;
8997  if ( !instantiation_name.empty() )
8998  test_case_name_stream << instantiation_name.c_str() << "/";
8999  test_case_name_stream << test_info->test_case_base_name.c_str();
9000 
9001  int i = 0;
9002  for (typename ParamGenerator<ParamType>::iterator param_it =
9003  generator.begin();
9004  param_it != generator.end(); ++param_it, ++i) {
9005  Message test_name_stream;
9006  test_name_stream << test_info->test_base_name.c_str() << "/" << i;
9007  ::testing::internal::MakeAndRegisterTestInfo(
9008  test_case_name_stream.GetString().c_str(),
9009  test_name_stream.GetString().c_str(),
9010  "", // test_case_comment
9011  "", // comment; TODO(vladl@google.com): provide parameter value
9012  // representation.
9013  GetTestCaseTypeId(),
9014  TestCase::SetUpTestCase,
9015  TestCase::TearDownTestCase,
9016  test_info->test_meta_factory->CreateTestFactory(*param_it));
9017  } // for param_it
9018  } // for gen_it
9019  } // for test_it
9020  } // RegisterTests
9021 
9022  private:
9023  // LocalTestInfo structure keeps information about a single test registered
9024  // with TEST_P macro.
9025  struct TestInfo {
9026  TestInfo(const char* a_test_case_base_name,
9027  const char* a_test_base_name,
9028  TestMetaFactoryBase<ParamType>* a_test_meta_factory) :
9029  test_case_base_name(a_test_case_base_name),
9030  test_base_name(a_test_base_name),
9031  test_meta_factory(a_test_meta_factory) {}
9032 
9033  const String test_case_base_name;
9034  const String test_base_name;
9035  const scoped_ptr<TestMetaFactoryBase<ParamType> > test_meta_factory;
9036  };
9037  typedef ::std::vector<linked_ptr<TestInfo> > TestInfoContainer;
9038  // Keeps pairs of <Instantiation name, Sequence generator creation function>
9039  // received from INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P macros.
9040  typedef ::std::vector<std::pair<String, GeneratorCreationFunc*> >
9041  InstantiationContainer;
9042 
9043  const String test_case_name_;
9044  TestInfoContainer tests_;
9045  InstantiationContainer instantiations_;
9046 
9047  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ParameterizedTestCaseInfo);
9048 }; // class ParameterizedTestCaseInfo
9049 
9050 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
9051 //
9052 // ParameterizedTestCaseRegistry contains a map of ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase
9053 // classes accessed by test case names. TEST_P and INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P
9054 // macros use it to locate their corresponding ParameterizedTestCaseInfo
9055 // descriptors.
9056 class ParameterizedTestCaseRegistry {
9057  public:
9058  ParameterizedTestCaseRegistry() {}
9059  ~ParameterizedTestCaseRegistry() {
9060  for (TestCaseInfoContainer::iterator it = test_case_infos_.begin();
9061  it != test_case_infos_.end(); ++it) {
9062  delete *it;
9063  }
9064  }
9065 
9066  // Looks up or creates and returns a structure containing information about
9067  // tests and instantiations of a particular test case.
9068  template <class TestCase>
9069  ParameterizedTestCaseInfo<TestCase>* GetTestCasePatternHolder(
9070  const char* test_case_name,
9071  const char* file,
9072  int line) {
9073  ParameterizedTestCaseInfo<TestCase>* typed_test_info = NULL;
9074  for (TestCaseInfoContainer::iterator it = test_case_infos_.begin();
9075  it != test_case_infos_.end(); ++it) {
9076  if ((*it)->GetTestCaseName() == test_case_name) {
9077  if ((*it)->GetTestCaseTypeId() != GetTypeId<TestCase>()) {
9078  // Complain about incorrect usage of Google Test facilities
9079  // and terminate the program since we cannot guaranty correct
9080  // test case setup and tear-down in this case.
9081  ReportInvalidTestCaseType(test_case_name, file, line);
9082  abort();
9083  } else {
9084  // At this point we are sure that the object we found is of the same
9085  // type we are looking for, so we downcast it to that type
9086  // without further checks.
9087  typed_test_info = CheckedDowncastToActualType<
9088  ParameterizedTestCaseInfo<TestCase> >(*it);
9089  }
9090  break;
9091  }
9092  }
9093  if (typed_test_info == NULL) {
9094  typed_test_info = new ParameterizedTestCaseInfo<TestCase>(test_case_name);
9095  test_case_infos_.push_back(typed_test_info);
9096  }
9097  return typed_test_info;
9098  }
9099  void RegisterTests() {
9100  for (TestCaseInfoContainer::iterator it = test_case_infos_.begin();
9101  it != test_case_infos_.end(); ++it) {
9102  (*it)->RegisterTests();
9103  }
9104  }
9105 
9106  private:
9107  typedef ::std::vector<ParameterizedTestCaseInfoBase*> TestCaseInfoContainer;
9108 
9109  TestCaseInfoContainer test_case_infos_;
9110 
9111  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ParameterizedTestCaseRegistry);
9112 };

11946 #if GTEST_HAS_COMBINE
11947 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
11948 //
11949 // Generates values from the Cartesian product of values produced
11950 // by the argument generators.
11951 //
11952 template <typename T1, typename T2>
11953 class CartesianProductGenerator2
11954  : public ParamGeneratorInterface< ::std::tr1::tuple<T1, T2> > {
11955  public:
11956  typedef ::std::tr1::tuple<T1, T2> ParamType;
11957 
11958  CartesianProductGenerator2(const ParamGenerator<T1>& g1,
11959  const ParamGenerator<T2>& g2)
11960  : g1_(g1), g2_(g2) {}
11961  virtual ~CartesianProductGenerator2() {}
11962 
11963  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>* Begin() const {
11964  return new Iterator(this, g1_, g1_.begin(), g2_, g2_.begin());
11965  }
11966  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>* End() const {
11967  return new Iterator(this, g1_, g1_.end(), g2_, g2_.end());
11968  }
11969 
11970  private:
11971  class Iterator : public ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType> {
11972  public:
11973  Iterator(const ParamGeneratorInterface<ParamType>* base,
11974  const ParamGenerator<T1>& g1,
11975  const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator& current1,
11976  const ParamGenerator<T2>& g2,
11977  const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator& current2)
11978  : base_(base),
11979  begin1_(g1.begin()), end1_(g1.end()), current1_(current1),
11980  begin2_(g2.begin()), end2_(g2.end()), current2_(current2) {
11981  ComputeCurrentValue();
11982  }
11983  virtual ~Iterator() {}
11984 
11985  virtual const ParamGeneratorInterface<ParamType>* BaseGenerator() const {
11986  return base_;
11987  }
11988  // Advance should not be called on beyond-of-range iterators
11989  // so no component iterators must be beyond end of range, either.
11990  virtual void Advance() {
11991  assert(!AtEnd());
11992  ++current2_;
11993  if (current2_ == end2_) {
11994  current2_ = begin2_;
11995  ++current1_;
11996  }
11997  ComputeCurrentValue();
11998  }
11999  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>* Clone() const {
12000  return new Iterator(*this);
12001  }
12002  virtual const ParamType* Current() const { return &current_value_; }
12003  virtual bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>& other) const {
12004  // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
12005  // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
12006  GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
12007  << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
12008  << "from different generators." << std::endl;
12009  const Iterator* typed_other =
12010  CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other);
12011  // We must report iterators equal if they both point beyond their
12012  // respective ranges. That can happen in a variety of fashions,
12013  // so we have to consult AtEnd().
12014  return (AtEnd() && typed_other->AtEnd()) ||
12015  (
12016  current1_ == typed_other->current1_ &&
12017  current2_ == typed_other->current2_);
12018  }
12019 
12020  private:
12021  Iterator(const Iterator& other)
12022  : base_(other.base_),
12023  begin1_(other.begin1_),
12024  end1_(other.end1_),
12025  current1_(other.current1_),
12026  begin2_(other.begin2_),
12027  end2_(other.end2_),
12028  current2_(other.current2_) {
12029  ComputeCurrentValue();
12030  }
12031 
12032  void ComputeCurrentValue() {
12033  if (!AtEnd())
12034  current_value_ = ParamType(*current1_, *current2_);
12035  }
12036  bool AtEnd() const {
12037  // We must report iterator past the end of the range when either of the
12038  // component iterators has reached the end of its range.
12039  return
12040  current1_ == end1_ ||
12041  current2_ == end2_;
12042  }
12043 
12044  // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
12045  void operator=(const Iterator& other);
12046 
12047  const ParamGeneratorInterface<ParamType>* const base_;
12048  // begin[i]_ and end[i]_ define the i-th range that Iterator traverses.
12049  // current[i]_ is the actual traversing iterator.
12050  const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator begin1_;
12051  const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator end1_;
12052  typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator current1_;
12053  const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator begin2_;
12054  const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator end2_;
12055  typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator current2_;
12056  ParamType current_value_;
12057  }; // class CartesianProductGenerator2::Iterator
12058 
12059  // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
12060  void operator=(const CartesianProductGenerator2& other);
12061 
12062  const ParamGenerator<T1> g1_;
12063  const ParamGenerator<T2> g2_;
12064 }; // class CartesianProductGenerator2

12396  return base_;
12397  }
12398  // Advance should not be called on beyond-of-range iterators
12399  // so no component iterators must be beyond end of range, either.
12400  virtual void Advance() {
12401  assert(!AtEnd());
12402  ++current5_;
12403  if (current5_ == end5_) {
12404  current5_ = begin5_;
12405  ++current4_;
12406  }
12407  if (current4_ == end4_) {
12408  current4_ = begin4_;
12409  ++current3_;
12410  }

12414  }

12416  current2_ = begin2_;
12417  ++current1_;
12418  }

12423  }

12425  virtual bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>& other) const {
12426  // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
12427  // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
12428  GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
12429  << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
12430  << "from different generators." << std::endl;
12431  const Iterator* typed_other =
12432  CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other);
12433  // We must report iterators equal if they both point beyond their
12434  // respective ranges. That can happen in a variety of fashions,
12435  // so we have to consult AtEnd().
12436  return (AtEnd() && typed_other->AtEnd()) ||
12437  (
12438  current1_ == typed_other->current1_ &&
12439  current2_ == typed_other->current2_ &&
12440  current3_ == typed_other->current3_ &&
12441  current4_ == typed_other->current4_ &&
12442  current5_ == typed_other->current5_);

12467  if (!AtEnd())

12469  *current4_, *current5_);
12470  }
12471  bool AtEnd() const {
12472  // We must report iterator past the end of the range when either of the
12473  // component iterators has reached the end of its range.
12474  return
12475  current1_ == end1_ ||
12476  current2_ == end2_ ||
12477  current3_ == end3_ ||

13012  GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())

13435  virtual const ParamGeneratorInterface<ParamType>* BaseGenerator() const {
13436  return base_;
13437  }
13438  // Advance should not be called on beyond-of-range iterators
13439  // so no component iterators must be beyond end of range, either.
13440  virtual void Advance() {
13441  assert(!AtEnd());
13442  ++current10_;
13443  if (current10_ == end10_) {
13444  current10_ = begin10_;
13445  ++current9_;
13446  }
13447  if (current9_ == end9_) {
13448  current9_ = begin9_;
13449  ++current8_;
13450  }
13451  if (current8_ == end8_) {
13452  current8_ = begin8_;
13453  ++current7_;
13454  }
13455  if (current7_ == end7_) {
13456  current7_ = begin7_;
13457  ++current6_;
13458  }
13459  if (current6_ == end6_) {
13460  current6_ = begin6_;
13461  ++current5_;
13462  }
13463  if (current5_ == end5_) {
13464  current5_ = begin5_;
13465  ++current4_;
13466  }
13467  if (current4_ == end4_) {
13468  current4_ = begin4_;
13469  ++current3_;
13470  }
13471  if (current3_ == end3_) {
13472  current3_ = begin3_;
13473  ++current2_;
13474  }
13475  if (current2_ == end2_) {
13476  current2_ = begin2_;
13477  ++current1_;
13478  }
13479  ComputeCurrentValue();
13480  }
13481  virtual ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>* Clone() const {
13482  return new Iterator(*this);
13483  }
13484  virtual const ParamType* Current() const { return &current_value_; }
13485  virtual bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>& other) const {
13486  // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
13487  // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
13488  GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
13489  << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
13490  << "from different generators." << std::endl;
13491  const Iterator* typed_other =
13492  CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other);
13493  // We must report iterators equal if they both point beyond their
13494  // respective ranges. That can happen in a variety of fashions,
13495  // so we have to consult AtEnd().
13496  return (AtEnd() && typed_other->AtEnd()) ||
13497  (
13498  current1_ == typed_other->current1_ &&
13499  current2_ == typed_other->current2_ &&
13500  current3_ == typed_other->current3_ &&
13501  current4_ == typed_other->current4_ &&
13502  current5_ == typed_other->current5_ &&
13503  current6_ == typed_other->current6_ &&
13504  current7_ == typed_other->current7_ &&
13505  current8_ == typed_other->current8_ &&
13506  current9_ == typed_other->current9_ &&
13507  current10_ == typed_other->current10_);
13508  }
13509 
13510  private:
13511  Iterator(const Iterator& other)
13512  : base_(other.base_),
13513  begin1_(other.begin1_),
13514  end1_(other.end1_),
13515  current1_(other.current1_),
13516  begin2_(other.begin2_),
13517  end2_(other.end2_),
13518  current2_(other.current2_),
13519  begin3_(other.begin3_),
13520  end3_(other.end3_),
13521  current3_(other.current3_),
13522  begin4_(other.begin4_),
13523  end4_(other.end4_),
13524  current4_(other.current4_),
13525  begin5_(other.begin5_),
13526  end5_(other.end5_),
13527  current5_(other.current5_),
13528  begin6_(other.begin6_),
13529  end6_(other.end6_),
13530  current6_(other.current6_),
13531  begin7_(other.begin7_),
13532  end7_(other.end7_),
13533  current7_(other.current7_),
13534  begin8_(other.begin8_),
13535  end8_(other.end8_),
13536  current8_(other.current8_),
13537  begin9_(other.begin9_),
13538  end9_(other.end9_),
13539  current9_(other.current9_),
13540  begin10_(other.begin10_),
13541  end10_(other.end10_),
13542  current10_(other.current10_) {
13543  ComputeCurrentValue();
13544  }
13545 
13546  void ComputeCurrentValue() {
13547  if (!AtEnd())
13548  current_value_ = ParamType(*current1_, *current2_, *current3_,
13549  *current4_, *current5_, *current6_, *current7_, *current8_,
13550  *current9_, *current10_);
13551  }
13552  bool AtEnd() const {
13553  // We must report iterator past the end of the range when either of the
13554  // component iterators has reached the end of its range.
13555  return
13556  current1_ == end1_ ||
13557  current2_ == end2_ ||
13558  current3_ == end3_ ||
13559  current4_ == end4_ ||
13560  current5_ == end5_ ||
13561  current6_ == end6_ ||
13562  current7_ == end7_ ||
13563  current8_ == end8_ ||
13564  current9_ == end9_ ||
13565  current10_ == end10_;
13566  }
13567 
13568  // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
13569  void operator=(const Iterator& other);
13570 
13571  const ParamGeneratorInterface<ParamType>* const base_;
13572  // begin[i]_ and end[i]_ define the i-th range that Iterator traverses.
13573  // current[i]_ is the actual traversing iterator.
13574  const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator begin1_;
13575  const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator end1_;
13576  typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator current1_;
13577  const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator begin2_;
13578  const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator end2_;
13579  typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator current2_;
13580  const typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator begin3_;
13581  const typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator end3_;
13582  typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator current3_;
13583  const typename ParamGenerator<T4>::iterator begin4_;
13584  const typename ParamGenerator<T4>::iterator end4_;
13585  typename ParamGenerator<T4>::iterator current4_;
13586  const typename ParamGenerator<T5>::iterator begin5_;
13587  const typename ParamGenerator<T5>::iterator end5_;
13588  typename ParamGenerator<T5>::iterator current5_;
13589  const typename ParamGenerator<T6>::iterator begin6_;
13590  const typename ParamGenerator<T6>::iterator end6_;
13591  typename ParamGenerator<T6>::iterator current6_;
13592  const typename ParamGenerator<T7>::iterator begin7_;
13593  const typename ParamGenerator<T7>::iterator end7_;
13594  typename ParamGenerator<T7>::iterator current7_;
13595  const typename ParamGenerator<T8>::iterator begin8_;
13596  const typename ParamGenerator<T8>::iterator end8_;
13597  typename ParamGenerator<T8>::iterator current8_;
13598  const typename ParamGenerator<T9>::iterator begin9_;
13599  const typename ParamGenerator<T9>::iterator end9_;
13600  typename ParamGenerator<T9>::iterator current9_;
13601  const typename ParamGenerator<T10>::iterator begin10_;
13602  const typename ParamGenerator<T10>::iterator end10_;
13603  typename ParamGenerator<T10>::iterator current10_;
13604  ParamType current_value_;
13605  }; // class CartesianProductGenerator10::Iterator

13941 namespace testing {
13942 
13943 // Functions producing parameter generators.
13944 //
13945 // Google Test uses these generators to produce parameters for value-
13946 // parameterized tests. When a parameterized test case is instantiated
13947 // with a particular generator, Google Test creates and runs tests
13948 // for each element in the sequence produced by the generator.
13949 //
13950 // In the following sample, tests from test case FooTest are instantiated
13951 // each three times with parameter values 3, 5, and 8:
13952 //
13953 // class FooTest : public TestWithParam<int> { ... };
13954 //
13955 // TEST_P(FooTest, TestThis) {
13956 // }
13957 // TEST_P(FooTest, TestThat) {
13958 // }
13959 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(TestSequence, FooTest, Values(3, 5, 8));
13960 //
13961 
13962 // Range() returns generators providing sequences of values in a range.
13963 //
13964 // Synopsis:
13965 // Range(start, end)
13966 // - returns a generator producing a sequence of values {start, start+1,
13967 // start+2, ..., }.
13968 // Range(start, end, step)
13969 // - returns a generator producing a sequence of values {start, start+step,
13970 // start+step+step, ..., }.
13971 // Notes:
13972 // * The generated sequences never include end. For example, Range(1, 5)
13973 // returns a generator producing a sequence {1, 2, 3, 4}. Range(1, 9, 2)
13974 // returns a generator producing {1, 3, 5, 7}.
13975 // * start and end must have the same type. That type may be any integral or
13976 // floating-point type or a user defined type satisfying these conditions:
13977 // * It must be assignable (have operator=() defined).
13978 // * It must have operator+() (operator+(int-compatible type) for
13979 // two-operand version).
13980 // * It must have operator<() defined.
13981 // Elements in the resulting sequences will also have that type.
13982 // * Condition start < end must be satisfied in order for resulting sequences
13983 // to contain any elements.
13984 //
13985 template <typename T, typename IncrementT>
13986 internal::ParamGenerator<T> Range(T start, T end, IncrementT step) {
13987  return internal::ParamGenerator<T>(
13988  new internal::RangeGenerator<T, IncrementT>(start, end, step));
13989 }
13990 
13991 template <typename T>
13992 internal::ParamGenerator<T> Range(T start, T end) {
13993  return Range(start, end, 1);
13994 }
13995 
13996 // ValuesIn() function allows generation of tests with parameters coming from
13997 // a container.
13998 //
13999 // Synopsis:
14000 // ValuesIn(const T (&array)[N])
14001 // - returns a generator producing sequences with elements from
14002 // a C-style array.
14003 // ValuesIn(const Container& container)
14004 // - returns a generator producing sequences with elements from
14005 // an STL-style container.
14006 // ValuesIn(Iterator begin, Iterator end)
14007 // - returns a generator producing sequences with elements from
14008 // a range [begin, end) defined by a pair of STL-style iterators. These
14009 // iterators can also be plain C pointers.
14010 //
14011 // Please note that ValuesIn copies the values from the containers
14012 // passed in and keeps them to generate tests in RUN_ALL_TESTS().
14013 //
14014 // Examples:
14015 //
14016 // This instantiates tests from test case StringTest
14017 // each with C-string values of "foo", "bar", and "baz":
14018 //
14019 // const char* strings[] = {"foo", "bar", "baz"};
14020 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(StringSequence, SrtingTest, ValuesIn(strings));
14021 //
14022 // This instantiates tests from test case StlStringTest
14023 // each with STL strings with values "a" and "b":
14024 //
14025 // ::std::vector< ::std::string> GetParameterStrings() {
14026 // ::std::vector< ::std::string> v;
14027 // v.push_back("a");
14028 // v.push_back("b");
14029 // return v;
14030 // }
14031 //
14032 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(CharSequence,
14033 // StlStringTest,
14034 // ValuesIn(GetParameterStrings()));
14035 //
14036 //
14037 // This will also instantiate tests from CharTest
14038 // each with parameter values 'a' and 'b':
14039 //
14040 // ::std::list<char> GetParameterChars() {
14041 // ::std::list<char> list;
14042 // list.push_back('a');
14043 // list.push_back('b');
14044 // return list;
14045 // }
14046 // ::std::list<char> l = GetParameterChars();
14047 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(CharSequence2,
14048 // CharTest,
14049 // ValuesIn(l.begin(), l.end()));
14050 //
14051 template <typename ForwardIterator>
14052 internal::ParamGenerator<
14053  typename ::std::iterator_traits<ForwardIterator>::value_type> ValuesIn(
14054  ForwardIterator begin,
14055  ForwardIterator end) {
14056  typedef typename ::std::iterator_traits<ForwardIterator>::value_type
14057  ParamType;
14058  return internal::ParamGenerator<ParamType>(
14059  new internal::ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator<ParamType>(begin, end));
14060 }
14061 
14062 template <typename T, size_t N>
14063 internal::ParamGenerator<T> ValuesIn(const T (&array)[N]) {
14064  return ValuesIn(array, array + N);
14065 }
14066 
14067 template <class Container>
14068 internal::ParamGenerator<typename Container::value_type> ValuesIn(
14069  const Container& container) {
14070  return ValuesIn(container.begin(), container.end());
14071 }
14072 
14073 // Values() allows generating tests from explicitly specified list of
14074 // parameters.
14075 //
14076 // Synopsis:
14077 // Values(T v1, T v2, ..., T vN)
14078 // - returns a generator producing sequences with elements v1, v2, ..., vN.
14079 //
14080 // For example, this instantiates tests from test case BarTest each
14081 // with values "one", "two", and "three":
14082 //
14083 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(NumSequence, BarTest, Values("one", "two", "three"));
14084 //
14085 // This instantiates tests from test case BazTest each with values 1, 2, 3.5.
14086 // The exact type of values will depend on the type of parameter in BazTest.
14087 //
14088 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(FloatingNumbers, BazTest, Values(1, 2, 3.5));
14089 //
14090 // Currently, Values() supports from 1 to 50 parameters.
14091 //
14092 template <typename T1>
14093 internal::ValueArray1<T1> Values(T1 v1) {
14094  return internal::ValueArray1<T1>(v1);
14095 }
14096 
14097 template <typename T1, typename T2>
14098 internal::ValueArray2<T1, T2> Values(T1 v1, T2 v2) {
14099  return internal::ValueArray2<T1, T2>(v1, v2);
14100 }

14944 
14945 // Bool() allows generating tests with parameters in a set of (false, true).
14946 //
14947 // Synopsis:
14948 // Bool()
14949 // - returns a generator producing sequences with elements {false, true}.
14950 //
14951 // It is useful when testing code that depends on Boolean flags. Combinations
14952 // of multiple flags can be tested when several Bool()'s are combined using
14953 // Combine() function.
14954 //
14955 // In the following example all tests in the test case FlagDependentTest
14956 // will be instantiated twice with parameters false and true.
14957 //
14958 // class FlagDependentTest : public testing::TestWithParam<bool> {
14959 // virtual void SetUp() {
14960 // external_flag = GetParam();
14961 // }
14962 // }
14963 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(BoolSequence, FlagDependentTest, Bool());
14964 //
14965 inline internal::ParamGenerator<bool> Bool() {
14966  return Values(false, true);
14967 }
14968 
14969 #if GTEST_HAS_COMBINE
14970 // Combine() allows the user to combine two or more sequences to produce
14971 // values of a Cartesian product of those sequences' elements.
14972 //
14973 // Synopsis:
14974 // Combine(gen1, gen2, ..., genN)
14975 // - returns a generator producing sequences with elements coming from
14976 // the Cartesian product of elements from the sequences generated by
14977 // gen1, gen2, ..., genN. The sequence elements will have a type of
14978 // tuple<T1, T2, ..., TN> where T1, T2, ..., TN are the types
14979 // of elements from sequences produces by gen1, gen2, ..., genN.
14980 //
14981 // Combine can have up to 10 arguments. This number is currently limited
14982 // by the maximum number of elements in the tuple implementation used by Google
14983 // Test.
14984 //
14985 // Example:
14986 //
14987 // This will instantiate tests in test case AnimalTest each one with
14988 // the parameter values tuple("cat", BLACK), tuple("cat", WHITE),
14989 // tuple("dog", BLACK), and tuple("dog", WHITE):
14990 //
14991 // enum Color { BLACK, GRAY, WHITE };
14992 // class AnimalTest
14993 // : public testing::TestWithParam<tuple<const char*, Color> > {...};
14994 //
14995 // TEST_P(AnimalTest, AnimalLooksNice) {...}
14996 //
14997 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(AnimalVariations, AnimalTest,
14998 // Combine(Values("cat", "dog"),
14999 // Values(BLACK, WHITE)));
15000 //
15001 // This will instantiate tests in FlagDependentTest with all variations of two
15002 // Boolean flags:
15003 //
15004 // class FlagDependentTest
15005 // : public testing::TestWithParam<tuple(bool, bool)> > {
15006 // virtual void SetUp() {
15007 // // Assigns external_flag_1 and external_flag_2 values from the tuple.
15008 // tie(external_flag_1, external_flag_2) = GetParam();
15009 // }
15010 // };
15011 //
15012 // TEST_P(FlagDependentTest, TestFeature1) {
15013 // // Test your code using external_flag_1 and external_flag_2 here.
15014 // }
15015 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(TwoBoolSequence, FlagDependentTest,
15016 // Combine(Bool(), Bool()));
15017 //
15018 template <typename Generator1, typename Generator2>
15019 internal::CartesianProductHolder2<Generator1, Generator2> Combine(
15020  const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2) {
15021  return internal::CartesianProductHolder2<Generator1, Generator2>(
15022  g1, g2);
15023 }
15024 
15025 template <typename Generator1, typename Generator2, typename Generator3>
15026 internal::CartesianProductHolder3<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3> Combine(
15027  const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2, const Generator3& g3) {
15028  return internal::CartesianProductHolder3<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3>(
15029  g1, g2, g3);
15030 }
15031 
15032 template <typename Generator1, typename Generator2, typename Generator3,
15033  typename Generator4>
15034 internal::CartesianProductHolder4<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3,
15035  Generator4> Combine(
15036  const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2, const Generator3& g3,
15037  const Generator4& g4) {
15038  return internal::CartesianProductHolder4<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3,
15039  Generator4>(
15040  g1, g2, g3, g4);
15041 }
15042

15047  const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2, const Generator3& g3,
15048  const Generator4& g4, const Generator5& g5) {
15049  return internal::CartesianProductHolder5<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3,
15050  Generator4, Generator5>(
15051  g1, g2, g3, g4, g5);
15052 }

15091 template <typename Generator1, typename Generator2, typename Generator3,
15092  typename Generator4, typename Generator5, typename Generator6,
15093  typename Generator7, typename Generator8, typename Generator9>
15094 internal::CartesianProductHolder9<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3,
15095  Generator4, Generator5, Generator6, Generator7, Generator8,
15096  Generator9> Combine(
15097  const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2, const Generator3& g3,
15098  const Generator4& g4, const Generator5& g5, const Generator6& g6,
15099  const Generator7& g7, const Generator8& g8, const Generator9& g9) {
15100  return internal::CartesianProductHolder9<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3,
15101  Generator4, Generator5, Generator6, Generator7, Generator8, Generator9>(
15102  g1, g2, g3, g4, g5, g6, g7, g8, g9);
15103 }
15104 
15105 template <typename Generator1, typename Generator2, typename Generator3,
15106  typename Generator4, typename Generator5, typename Generator6,
15107  typename Generator7, typename Generator8, typename Generator9,
15108  typename Generator10>
15109 internal::CartesianProductHolder10<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3,
15110  Generator4, Generator5, Generator6, Generator7, Generator8, Generator9,
15111  Generator10> Combine(
15112  const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2, const Generator3& g3,
15113  const Generator4& g4, const Generator5& g5, const Generator6& g6,
15114  const Generator7& g7, const Generator8& g8, const Generator9& g9,
15115  const Generator10& g10) {
15116  return internal::CartesianProductHolder10<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3,
15117  Generator4, Generator5, Generator6, Generator7, Generator8, Generator9,
15118  Generator10>(
15119  g1, g2, g3, g4, g5, g6, g7, g8, g9, g10);
15120 }

15125 #define TEST_P(test_case_name, test_name) \
15126  class GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name) \
15127  : public test_case_name { \
15128  public: \
15129  GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name)() {} \
15130  virtual void TestBody(); \
15131  private: \
15132  static int AddToRegistry() { \
15133  ::testing::UnitTest::GetInstance()->parameterized_test_registry(). \
15134  GetTestCasePatternHolder<test_case_name>(\
15135  #test_case_name, __FILE__, __LINE__)->AddTestPattern(\
15136  #test_case_name, \
15137  #test_name, \
15138  new ::testing::internal::TestMetaFactory< \
15139  GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name)>()); \
15140  return 0; \
15141  } \
15142  static int gtest_registering_dummy_; \
15143  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(\
15144  GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name)); \
15145  }; \
15146  int GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, \
15147  test_name)::gtest_registering_dummy_ = \
15148  GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name)::AddToRegistry(); \
15149  void GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_case_name, test_name)::TestBody()
15150 
15151 #define INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(prefix, test_case_name, generator) \
15152  ::testing::internal::ParamGenerator<test_case_name::ParamType> \
15153  gtest_##prefix##test_case_name##_EvalGenerator_() { return generator; } \
15154  int gtest_##prefix##test_case_name##_dummy_ = \
15155  ::testing::UnitTest::GetInstance()->parameterized_test_registry(). \
15156  GetTestCasePatternHolder<test_case_name>(\
15157  #test_case_name, __FILE__, __LINE__)->AddTestCaseInstantiation(\
15158  #prefix, \
15159  &gtest_##prefix##test_case_name##_EvalGenerator_, \
15160  __FILE__, __LINE__)
15161 
15162 } // namespace testing

15164 #endif // GTEST_HAS_PARAM_TEST

15203 // When you need to test the private or protected members of a class,
15204 // use the FRIEND_TEST macro to declare your tests as friends of the
15205 // class. For example:
15206 //
15207 // class MyClass {
15208 // private:
15209 // void MyMethod();
15210 // FRIEND_TEST(MyClassTest, MyMethod);
15211 // };
15212 //
15213 // class MyClassTest : public testing::Test {
15214 // // ...
15215 // };
15216 //
15217 // TEST_F(MyClassTest, MyMethod) {
15218 // // Can call MyClass::MyMethod() here.
15219 // }
15220 
15221 #define FRIEND_TEST(test_case_name, test_name)\
15222 friend class test_case_name##_##test_name##_Test
15223 
15224 #endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_PROD_H_

15263 namespace testing {
15264 
15265 // A copyable object representing the result of a test part (i.e. an
15266 // assertion or an explicit FAIL(), ADD_FAILURE(), or SUCCESS()).
15267 //
15268 // Don't inherit from TestPartResult as its destructor is not virtual.
15269 class GTEST_API_ TestPartResult {
15270  public:
15271  // The possible outcomes of a test part (i.e. an assertion or an
15272  // explicit SUCCEED(), FAIL(), or ADD_FAILURE()).
15273  enum Type {
15274  kSuccess, // Succeeded.
15275  kNonFatalFailure, // Failed but the test can continue.
15276  kFatalFailure // Failed and the test should be terminated.
15277  };
15278 
15279  // C'tor. TestPartResult does NOT have a default constructor.
15280  // Always use this constructor (with parameters) to create a
15281  // TestPartResult object.
15282  TestPartResult(Type a_type,
15283  const char* a_file_name,
15284  int a_line_number,
15285  const char* a_message)
15286  : type_(a_type),
15287  file_name_(a_file_name),
15288  line_number_(a_line_number),
15289  summary_(ExtractSummary(a_message)),
15290  message_(a_message) {
15291  }
15292 
15293  // Gets the outcome of the test part.
15294  Type type() const { return type_; }
15295 
15296  // Gets the name of the source file where the test part took place, or
15297  // NULL if it's unknown.
15298  const char* file_name() const { return file_name_.c_str(); }
15299 
15300  // Gets the line in the source file where the test part took place,
15301  // or -1 if it's unknown.
15302  int line_number() const { return line_number_; }
15303 
15304  // Gets the summary of the failure message.
15305  const char* summary() const { return summary_.c_str(); }
15306 
15307  // Gets the message associated with the test part.
15308  const char* message() const { return message_.c_str(); }
15309 
15310  // Returns true iff the test part passed.
15311  bool passed() const { return type_ == kSuccess; }
15312 
15313  // Returns true iff the test part failed.
15314  bool failed() const { return type_ != kSuccess; }
15315 
15316  // Returns true iff the test part non-fatally failed.
15317  bool nonfatally_failed() const { return type_ == kNonFatalFailure; }
15318 
15319  // Returns true iff the test part fatally failed.
15320  bool fatally_failed() const { return type_ == kFatalFailure; }
15321  private:
15322  Type type_;
15323 
15324  // Gets the summary of the failure message by omitting the stack
15325  // trace in it.
15326  static internal::String ExtractSummary(const char* message);
15327 
15328  // The name of the source file where the test part took place, or
15329  // NULL if the source file is unknown.
15330  internal::String file_name_;
15331  // The line in the source file where the test part took place, or -1
15332  // if the line number is unknown.
15333  int line_number_;
15334  internal::String summary_; // The test failure summary.
15335  internal::String message_; // The test failure message.
15336 };
15337 
15338 // Prints a TestPartResult object.
15339 std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os, const TestPartResult& result);
15340 
15341 // An array of TestPartResult objects.
15342 //
15343 // Don't inherit from TestPartResultArray as its destructor is not
15344 // virtual.
15345 class GTEST_API_ TestPartResultArray {
15346  public:
15347  TestPartResultArray() {}
15348 
15349  // Appends the given TestPartResult to the array.
15350  void Append(const TestPartResult& result);
15351 
15352  // Returns the TestPartResult at the given index (0-based).
15353  const TestPartResult& GetTestPartResult(int index) const;
15354 
15355  // Returns the number of TestPartResult objects in the array.
15356  int size() const;
15357 
15358  private:
15359  std::vector<TestPartResult> array_;
15360 
15361  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(TestPartResultArray);
15362 };
15363 
15364 // This interface knows how to report a test part result.
15365 class GTEST_API_ TestPartResultReporterInterface {
15366  public:
15367  virtual ~TestPartResultReporterInterface() {}
15368 
15369  virtual void ReportTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& result) = 0;
15370 };

15374 // This helper class is used by {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NO_FATAL_FAILURE to check if a
15375 // statement generates new fatal failures. To do so it registers itself as the
15376 // current test part result reporter. Besides checking if fatal failures were
15377 // reported, it only delegates the reporting to the former result reporter.
15378 // The original result reporter is restored in the destructor.
15379 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
15380 class GTEST_API_ HasNewFatalFailureHelper
15381  : public TestPartResultReporterInterface {
15382  public:
15383  HasNewFatalFailureHelper();
15384  virtual ~HasNewFatalFailureHelper();
15385  virtual void ReportTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& result);
15386  bool has_new_fatal_failure() const { return has_new_fatal_failure_; }
15387  private:
15388  bool has_new_fatal_failure_;
15389  TestPartResultReporterInterface* original_reporter_;
15390 
15391  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(HasNewFatalFailureHelper);
15392 };

15430 #ifndef GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_TYPED_TEST_H_
15431 #define GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_TYPED_TEST_H_
15432 
15433 // This header implements typed tests and type-parameterized tests.
15434 
15435 // Typed (aka type-driven) tests repeat the same test for types in a
15436 // list. You must know which types you want to test with when writing
15437 // typed tests. Here's how you do it:
15438 
15439 #if 0
15440 
15441 // First, define a fixture class template. It should be parameterized
15442 // by a type. Remember to derive it from testing::Test.
15443 template <typename T>
15444 class FooTest : public testing::Test {
15445  public:
15446  ...
15447  typedef std::list<T> List;
15448  static T shared_;
15449  T value_;
15450 };
15451 
15452 // Next, associate a list of types with the test case, which will be
15453 // repeated for each type in the list. The typedef is necessary for
15454 // the macro to parse correctly.
15455 typedef testing::Types<char, int, unsigned int> MyTypes;
15456 TYPED_TEST_CASE(FooTest, MyTypes);
15457 
15458 // If the type list contains only one type, you can write that type
15459 // directly without Types<...>:
15460 // TYPED_TEST_CASE(FooTest, int);
15461 
15462 // Then, use TYPED_TEST() instead of TEST_F() to define as many typed
15463 // tests for this test case as you want.
15464 TYPED_TEST(FooTest, DoesBlah) {
15465  // Inside a test, refer to TypeParam to get the type parameter.
15466  // Since we are inside a derived class template, C++ requires use to
15467  // visit the members of FooTest via 'this'.
15468  TypeParam n = this->value_;
15469 
15470  // To visit static members of the fixture, add the TestFixture::
15471  // prefix.
15472  n += TestFixture::shared_;
15473 
15474  // To refer to typedefs in the fixture, add the "typename
15475  // TestFixture::" prefix.
15476  typename TestFixture::List values;
15477  values.push_back(n);
15478  ...
15479 }
15480 
15481 TYPED_TEST(FooTest, HasPropertyA) { ... }
15482 
15483 #endif // 0
15484 
15485 // Type-parameterized tests are abstract test patterns parameterized
15486 // by a type. Compared with typed tests, type-parameterized tests
15487 // allow you to define the test pattern without knowing what the type
15488 // parameters are. The defined pattern can be instantiated with
15489 // different types any number of times, in any number of translation
15490 // units.
15491 //
15492 // If you are designing an interface or concept, you can define a
15493 // suite of type-parameterized tests to verify properties that any
15494 // valid implementation of the interface/concept should have. Then,
15495 // each implementation can easily instantiate the test suite to verify
15496 // that it conforms to the requirements, without having to write
15497 // similar tests repeatedly. Here's an example:
15498 
15499 #if 0
15500 
15501 // First, define a fixture class template. It should be parameterized
15502 // by a type. Remember to derive it from testing::Test.
15503 template <typename T>
15504 class FooTest : public testing::Test {
15505  ...
15506 };
15507 
15508 // Next, declare that you will define a type-parameterized test case
15509 // (the _P suffix is for "parameterized" or "pattern", whichever you
15510 // prefer):
15511 TYPED_TEST_CASE_P(FooTest);
15512 
15513 // Then, use TYPED_TEST_P() to define as many type-parameterized tests
15514 // for this type-parameterized test case as you want.
15515 TYPED_TEST_P(FooTest, DoesBlah) {
15516  // Inside a test, refer to TypeParam to get the type parameter.
15517  TypeParam n = 0;
15518  ...
15519 }
15520 
15521 TYPED_TEST_P(FooTest, HasPropertyA) { ... }
15522 
15523 // Now the tricky part: you need to register all test patterns before
15524 // you can instantiate them. The first argument of the macro is the
15525 // test case name; the rest are the names of the tests in this test
15526 // case.
15527 REGISTER_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P(FooTest,
15528  DoesBlah, HasPropertyA);
15529 
15530 // Finally, you are free to instantiate the pattern with the types you
15531 // want. If you put the above code in a header file, you can #include
15532 // it in multiple C++ source files and instantiate it multiple times.
15533 //
15534 // To distinguish different instances of the pattern, the first
15535 // argument to the INSTANTIATE_* macro is a prefix that will be added
15536 // to the actual test case name. Remember to pick unique prefixes for
15537 // different instances.
15538 typedef testing::Types<char, int, unsigned int> MyTypes;
15539 INSTANTIATE_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P(My, FooTest, MyTypes);
15540 
15541 // If the type list contains only one type, you can write that type
15542 // directly without Types<...>:
15543 // INSTANTIATE_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P(My, FooTest, int);
15544 
15545 #endif // 0
15546 
15547 
15548 // Implements typed tests.
15549 
15550 #if GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST
15551 
15552 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
15553 //
15554 // Expands to the name of the typedef for the type parameters of the
15555 // given test case.
15556 #define GTEST_TYPE_PARAMS_(TestCaseName) gtest_type_params_##TestCaseName##_
15557 
15558 // The 'Types' template argument below must have spaces around it
15559 // since some compilers may choke on '>>' when passing a template
15560 // instance (e.g. Types<int>)
15561 #define TYPED_TEST_CASE(CaseName, Types) \
15562  typedef ::testing::internal::TypeList< Types >::type \
15563  GTEST_TYPE_PARAMS_(CaseName)
15564 
15565 #define TYPED_TEST(CaseName, TestName) \
15566  template <typename gtest_TypeParam_> \
15567  class GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(CaseName, TestName) \
15568  : public CaseName<gtest_TypeParam_> { \
15569  private: \
15570  typedef CaseName<gtest_TypeParam_> TestFixture; \
15571  typedef gtest_TypeParam_ TypeParam; \
15572  virtual void TestBody(); \
15573  }; \
15574  bool gtest_##CaseName##_##TestName##_registered_ = \
15575  ::testing::internal::TypeParameterizedTest< \
15576  CaseName, \
15577  ::testing::internal::TemplateSel< \
15578  GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(CaseName, TestName)>, \
15579  GTEST_TYPE_PARAMS_(CaseName)>::Register(\
15580  "", #CaseName, #TestName, 0); \
15581  template <typename gtest_TypeParam_> \
15582  void GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(CaseName, TestName)<gtest_TypeParam_>::TestBody()
15583 
15584 #endif // GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST
15585 
15586 // Implements type-parameterized tests.
15587 
15588 #if GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST_P
15589 
15590 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
15591 //
15592 // Expands to the namespace name that the type-parameterized tests for
15593 // the given type-parameterized test case are defined in. The exact
15594 // name of the namespace is subject to change without notice.
15595 #define GTEST_CASE_NAMESPACE_(TestCaseName) \
15596  gtest_case_##TestCaseName##_
15597 
15598 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
15599 //
15600 // Expands to the name of the variable used to remember the names of
15601 // the defined tests in the given test case.
15602 #define GTEST_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P_STATE_(TestCaseName) \
15603  gtest_typed_test_case_p_state_##TestCaseName##_
15604 
15605 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE DIRECTLY.
15606 //
15607 // Expands to the name of the variable used to remember the names of
15608 // the registered tests in the given test case.
15609 #define GTEST_REGISTERED_TEST_NAMES_(TestCaseName) \
15610  gtest_registered_test_names_##TestCaseName##_
15611 
15612 // The variables defined in the type-parameterized test macros are
15613 // static as typically these macros are used in a .h file that can be
15614 // #included in multiple translation units linked together.
15615 #define TYPED_TEST_CASE_P(CaseName) \
15616  static ::testing::internal::TypedTestCasePState \
15617  GTEST_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P_STATE_(CaseName)
15618 
15619 #define TYPED_TEST_P(CaseName, TestName) \
15620  namespace GTEST_CASE_NAMESPACE_(CaseName) { \
15621  template <typename gtest_TypeParam_> \
15622  class TestName : public CaseName<gtest_TypeParam_> { \
15623  private: \
15624  typedef CaseName<gtest_TypeParam_> TestFixture; \
15625  typedef gtest_TypeParam_ TypeParam; \
15626  virtual void TestBody(); \
15627  }; \
15628  static bool gtest_##TestName##_defined_ = \
15629  GTEST_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P_STATE_(CaseName).AddTestName(\
15630  __FILE__, __LINE__, #CaseName, #TestName); \
15631  } \
15632  template <typename gtest_TypeParam_> \
15633  void GTEST_CASE_NAMESPACE_(CaseName)::TestName<gtest_TypeParam_>::TestBody()
15634 
15635 #define REGISTER_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P(CaseName, ...) \
15636  namespace GTEST_CASE_NAMESPACE_(CaseName) { \
15637  typedef ::testing::internal::Templates<__VA_ARGS__>::type gtest_AllTests_; \
15638  } \
15639  static const char* const GTEST_REGISTERED_TEST_NAMES_(CaseName) = \
15640  GTEST_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P_STATE_(CaseName).VerifyRegisteredTestNames(\
15641  __FILE__, __LINE__, #__VA_ARGS__)
15642 
15643 // The 'Types' template argument below must have spaces around it
15644 // since some compilers may choke on '>>' when passing a template
15645 // instance (e.g. Types<int>)
15646 #define INSTANTIATE_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P(Prefix, CaseName, Types) \
15647  bool gtest_##Prefix##_##CaseName = \
15648  ::testing::internal::TypeParameterizedTestCase<CaseName, \
15649  GTEST_CASE_NAMESPACE_(CaseName)::gtest_AllTests_, \
15650  ::testing::internal::TypeList< Types >::type>::Register(\
15651  #Prefix, #CaseName, GTEST_REGISTERED_TEST_NAMES_(CaseName))
15652 
15653 #endif // GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST_P
15654 
15655 #endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_TYPED_TEST_H_
15656 
15657 // Depending on the platform, different string classes are available.
15658 // On Linux, in addition to ::std::string, Google also makes use of
15659 // class ::string, which has the same interface as ::std::string, but
15660 // has a different implementation.
15661 //
15662 // The user can define GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING to 1 to indicate that
15663 // ::string is available AND is a distinct type to ::std::string, or
15664 // define it to 0 to indicate otherwise.
15665 //
15666 // If the user's ::std::string and ::string are the same class due to
15667 // aliasing, he should define GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING to 0.
15668 //
15669 // If the user doesn't define GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING, it is defined
15670 // heuristically.
15671

15752 // Converts a streamable value to a String. A NULL pointer is
15753 // converted to "(null)". When the input value is a ::string,
15754 // ::std::string, ::wstring, or ::std::wstring object, each NUL
15755 // character in it is replaced with "\\0".
15756 // Declared in gtest-internal.h but defined here, so that it has access
15757 // to the definition of the Message class, required by the ARM
15758 // compiler.
15759 template <typename T>
15760 String StreamableToString(const T& streamable) {
15761  return (Message() << streamable).GetString();
15762 }

15765 
15766 // A class for indicating whether an assertion was successful. When
15767 // the assertion wasn't successful, the AssertionResult object
15768 // remembers a non-empty message that describes how it failed.
15769 //
15770 // To create an instance of this class, use one of the factory functions
15771 // (AssertionSuccess() and AssertionFailure()).
15772 //
15773 // This class is useful for two purposes:
15774 // 1. Defining predicate functions to be used with Boolean test assertions
15775 // EXPECT_TRUE/EXPECT_FALSE and their ASSERT_ counterparts
15776 // 2. Defining predicate-format functions to be
15777 // used with predicate assertions (ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT*, etc).
15778 //
15779 // For example, if you define IsEven predicate:
15780 //
15781 // testing::AssertionResult IsEven(int n) {
15782 // if ((n % 2) == 0)
15783 // return testing::AssertionSuccess();
15784 // else
15785 // return testing::AssertionFailure() << n << " is odd";
15786 // }
15787 //
15788 // Then the failed expectation EXPECT_TRUE(IsEven(Fib(5)))
15789 // will print the message
15790 //
15791 // Value of: IsEven(Fib(5))
15792 // Actual: false (5 is odd)
15793 // Expected: true
15794 //
15795 // instead of a more opaque
15796 //
15797 // Value of: IsEven(Fib(5))
15798 // Actual: false
15799 // Expected: true
15800 //
15801 // in case IsEven is a simple Boolean predicate.
15802 //
15803 // If you expect your predicate to be reused and want to support informative
15804 // messages in EXPECT_FALSE and ASSERT_FALSE (negative assertions show up
15805 // about half as often as positive ones in our tests), supply messages for
15806 // both success and failure cases:
15807 //
15808 // testing::AssertionResult IsEven(int n) {
15809 // if ((n % 2) == 0)
15810 // return testing::AssertionSuccess() << n << " is even";
15811 // else
15812 // return testing::AssertionFailure() << n << " is odd";
15813 // }
15814 //
15815 // Then a statement EXPECT_FALSE(IsEven(Fib(6))) will print
15816 //
15817 // Value of: IsEven(Fib(6))
15818 // Actual: true (8 is even)
15819 // Expected: false
15820 //
15821 // NB: Predicates that support negative Boolean assertions have reduced
15822 // performance in positive ones so be careful not to use them in tests
15823 // that have lots (tens of thousands) of positive Boolean assertions.
15824 //
15825 // To use this class with EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT assertions such as:
15826 //
15827 // // Verifies that Foo() returns an even number.
15828 // EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT1(IsEven, Foo());
15829 //
15830 // you need to define:
15831 //
15832 // testing::AssertionResult IsEven(const char* expr, int n) {
15833 // if ((n % 2) == 0)
15834 // return testing::AssertionSuccess();
15835 // else
15836 // return testing::AssertionFailure()
15837 // << "Expected: " << expr << " is even\n Actual: it's " << n;
15838 // }
15839 //
15840 // If Foo() returns 5, you will see the following message:
15841 //
15842 // Expected: Foo() is even
15843 // Actual: it's 5
15844 //
15845 class GTEST_API_ AssertionResult {
15846  public:
15847  // Copy constructor.
15848  // Used in EXPECT_TRUE/FALSE(assertion_result).
15849  AssertionResult(const AssertionResult& other);
15850  // Used in the EXPECT_TRUE/FALSE(bool_expression).
15851  explicit AssertionResult(bool success) : success_(success) {}
15852 
15853  // Returns true iff the assertion succeeded.
15854  operator bool() const { return success_; } // NOLINT
15855 
15856  // Returns the assertion's negation. Used with EXPECT/ASSERT_FALSE.
15857  AssertionResult operator!() const;
15858 
15859  // Returns the text streamed into this AssertionResult. Test assertions
15860  // use it when they fail (i.e., the predicate's outcome doesn't match the
15861  // assertion's expectation). When nothing has been streamed into the
15862  // object, returns an empty string.
15863  const char* message() const {
15864  return message_.get() != NULL && message_->c_str() != NULL ?
15865  message_->c_str() : "";
15866  }
15867  // TODO(vladl@google.com): Remove this after making sure no clients use it.
15868  // Deprecated; please use message() instead.
15869  const char* failure_message() const { return message(); }
15870 
15871  // Streams a custom failure message into this object.
15872  template <typename T> AssertionResult& operator<<(const T& value);
15873 
15874  private:
15875  // No implementation - we want AssertionResult to be
15876  // copy-constructible but not assignable.
15877  void operator=(const AssertionResult& other);
15878 
15879  // Stores result of the assertion predicate.
15880  bool success_;
15881  // Stores the message describing the condition in case the expectation
15882  // construct is not satisfied with the predicate's outcome.
15883  // Referenced via a pointer to avoid taking too much stack frame space
15884  // with test assertions.
15885  internal::scoped_ptr<internal::String> message_;
15886 }; // class AssertionResult
15887 
15888 // Streams a custom failure message into this object.
15889 template <typename T>
15890 AssertionResult& AssertionResult::operator<<(const T& value) {
15891  Message msg;
15892  if (message_.get() != NULL)
15893  msg << *message_;
15894  msg << value;
15895  message_.reset(new internal::String(msg.GetString()));
15896  return *this;
15897 }
15898 
15899 // Makes a successful assertion result.
15900 GTEST_API_ AssertionResult AssertionSuccess();
15901 
15902 // Makes a failed assertion result.
15903 GTEST_API_ AssertionResult AssertionFailure();
15904 
15905 // Makes a failed assertion result with the given failure message.
15906 // Deprecated; use AssertionFailure() << msg.
15907 GTEST_API_ AssertionResult AssertionFailure(const Message& msg);

15909 // The abstract class that all tests inherit from.
15910 //
15911 // In Google Test, a unit test program contains one or many TestCases, and
15912 // each TestCase contains one or many Tests.
15913 //
15914 // When you define a test using the TEST macro, you don't need to
15915 // explicitly derive from Test - the TEST macro automatically does
15916 // this for you.
15917 //
15918 // The only time you derive from Test is when defining a test fixture
15919 // to be used a TEST_F. For example:
15920 //
15921 // class FooTest : public testing::Test {
15922 // protected:
15923 // virtual void SetUp() { ... }
15924 // virtual void TearDown() { ... }
15925 // ...
15926 // };
15927 //
15928 // TEST_F(FooTest, Bar) { ... }
15929 // TEST_F(FooTest, Baz) { ... }
15930 //
15931 // Test is not copyable.
15932 class GTEST_API_ Test {
15933  public:
15934  friend class internal::TestInfoImpl;
15935 
15936  // Defines types for pointers to functions that set up and tear down
15937  // a test case.
15938  typedef internal::SetUpTestCaseFunc SetUpTestCaseFunc;
15939  typedef internal::TearDownTestCaseFunc TearDownTestCaseFunc;
15940 
15941  // The d'tor is virtual as we intend to inherit from Test.
15942  virtual ~Test();
15943 
15944  // Sets up the stuff shared by all tests in this test case.
15945  //
15946  // Google Test will call Foo::SetUpTestCase() before running the first
15947  // test in test case Foo. Hence a sub-class can define its own
15948  // SetUpTestCase() method to shadow the one defined in the super
15949  // class.
15950  static void SetUpTestCase() {}
15951 
15952  // Tears down the stuff shared by all tests in this test case.
15953  //
15954  // Google Test will call Foo::TearDownTestCase() after running the last
15955  // test in test case Foo. Hence a sub-class can define its own
15956  // TearDownTestCase() method to shadow the one defined in the super
15957  // class.
15958  static void TearDownTestCase() {}
15959 
15960  // Returns true iff the current test has a fatal failure.
15961  static bool HasFatalFailure();
15962 
15963  // Returns true iff the current test has a non-fatal failure.
15964  static bool HasNonfatalFailure();
15965 
15966  // Returns true iff the current test has a (either fatal or
15967  // non-fatal) failure.
15968  static bool HasFailure() { return HasFatalFailure() || HasNonfatalFailure(); }
15969 
15970  // Logs a property for the current test. Only the last value for a given
15971  // key is remembered.
15972  // These are public static so they can be called from utility functions
15973  // that are not members of the test fixture.
15974  // The arguments are const char* instead strings, as Google Test is used
15975  // on platforms where string doesn't compile.
15976  //
15977  // Note that a driving consideration for these RecordProperty methods
15978  // was to produce xml output suited to the Greenspan charting utility,
15979  // which at present will only chart values that fit in a 32-bit int. It
15980  // is the user's responsibility to restrict their values to 32-bit ints
15981  // if they intend them to be used with Greenspan.
15982  static void RecordProperty(const char* key, const char* value);
15983  static void RecordProperty(const char* key, int value);
15984 
15985  protected:
15986  // Creates a Test object.
15987  Test();
15988 
15989  // Sets up the test fixture.
15990  virtual void SetUp();
15991 
15992  // Tears down the test fixture.
15993  virtual void TearDown();
15994 
15995  private:
15996  // Returns true iff the current test has the same fixture class as
15997  // the first test in the current test case.
15998  static bool HasSameFixtureClass();
15999 
16000  // Runs the test after the test fixture has been set up.
16001  //
16002  // A sub-class must implement this to define the test logic.
16003  //
16004  // DO NOT OVERRIDE THIS FUNCTION DIRECTLY IN A USER PROGRAM.
16005  // Instead, use the TEST or TEST_F macro.
16006  virtual void TestBody() = 0;
16007 
16008  // Sets up, executes, and tears down the test.
16009  void Run();
16010 
16011  // Uses a GTestFlagSaver to save and restore all Google Test flags.
16012  const internal::GTestFlagSaver* const gtest_flag_saver_;
16013 
16014  // Often a user mis-spells SetUp() as Setup() and spends a long time
16015  // wondering why it is never called by Google Test. The declaration of
16016  // the following method is solely for catching such an error at
16017  // compile time:
16018  //
16019  // - The return type is deliberately chosen to be not void, so it
16020  // will be a conflict if a user declares void Setup() in his test
16021  // fixture.
16022  //
16023  // - This method is private, so it will be another compiler error
16024  // if a user calls it from his test fixture.
16025  //
16026  // DO NOT OVERRIDE THIS FUNCTION.
16027  //
16028  // If you see an error about overriding the following function or
16029  // about it being private, you have mis-spelled SetUp() as Setup().
16030  struct Setup_should_be_spelled_SetUp {};
16031  virtual Setup_should_be_spelled_SetUp* Setup() { return NULL; }
16032 
16033  // We disallow copying Tests.
16034  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(Test);
16035 };

16039 // A copyable object representing a user specified test property which can be
16040 // output as a key/value string pair.
16041 //
16042 // Don't inherit from TestProperty as its destructor is not virtual.
16043 class TestProperty {
16044  public:
16045  // C'tor. TestProperty does NOT have a default constructor.
16046  // Always use this constructor (with parameters) to create a
16047  // TestProperty object.
16048  TestProperty(const char* a_key, const char* a_value) :
16049  key_(a_key), value_(a_value) {
16050  }
16051 
16052  // Gets the user supplied key.
16053  const char* key() const {
16054  return key_.c_str();
16055  }
16056 
16057  // Gets the user supplied value.
16058  const char* value() const {
16059  return value_.c_str();
16060  }
16061 
16062  // Sets a new value, overriding the one supplied in the constructor.
16063  void SetValue(const char* new_value) {
16064  value_ = new_value;
16065  }
16066 
16067  private:
16068  // The key supplied by the user.
16069  internal::String key_;
16070  // The value supplied by the user.
16071  internal::String value_;
16072 };

16074 // The result of a single Test. This includes a list of
16075 // TestPartResults, a list of TestProperties, a count of how many
16076 // death tests there are in the Test, and how much time it took to run
16077 // the Test.
16078 //
16079 // TestResult is not copyable.
16080 class GTEST_API_ TestResult {
16081  public:
16082  // Creates an empty TestResult.
16083  TestResult();
16084 
16085  // D'tor. Do not inherit from TestResult.
16086  ~TestResult();
16087 
16088  // Gets the number of all test parts. This is the sum of the number
16089  // of successful test parts and the number of failed test parts.
16090  int total_part_count() const;
16091 
16092  // Returns the number of the test properties.
16093  int test_property_count() const;
16094 
16095  // Returns true iff the test passed (i.e. no test part failed).
16096  bool Passed() const { return !Failed(); }
16097 
16098  // Returns true iff the test failed.
16099  bool Failed() const;
16100 
16101  // Returns true iff the test fatally failed.
16102  bool HasFatalFailure() const;
16103 
16104  // Returns true iff the test has a non-fatal failure.
16105  bool HasNonfatalFailure() const;
16106 
16107  // Returns the elapsed time, in milliseconds.
16108  TimeInMillis elapsed_time() const { return elapsed_time_; }
16109 
16110  // Returns the i-th test part result among all the results. i can range
16111  // from 0 to test_property_count() - 1. If i is not in that range, aborts
16112  // the program.
16113  const TestPartResult& GetTestPartResult(int i) const;
16114 
16115  // Returns the i-th test property. i can range from 0 to
16116  // test_property_count() - 1. If i is not in that range, aborts the
16117  // program.
16118  const TestProperty& GetTestProperty(int i) const;
16119 
16120  private:
16121  friend class TestInfo;
16122  friend class UnitTest;
16123  friend class internal::DefaultGlobalTestPartResultReporter;
16124  friend class internal::ExecDeathTest;
16125  friend class internal::TestInfoImpl;
16126  friend class internal::TestResultAccessor;
16127  friend class internal::UnitTestImpl;
16128  friend class internal::WindowsDeathTest;
16129 
16130  // Gets the vector of TestPartResults.
16131  const std::vector<TestPartResult>& test_part_results() const {
16132  return test_part_results_;
16133  }
16134 
16135  // Gets the vector of TestProperties.
16136  const std::vector<TestProperty>& test_properties() const {
16137  return test_properties_;
16138  }
16139 
16140  // Sets the elapsed time.
16141  void set_elapsed_time(TimeInMillis elapsed) { elapsed_time_ = elapsed; }
16142 
16143  // Adds a test property to the list. The property is validated and may add
16144  // a non-fatal failure if invalid (e.g., if it conflicts with reserved
16145  // key names). If a property is already recorded for the same key, the
16146  // value will be updated, rather than storing multiple values for the same
16147  // key.
16148  void RecordProperty(const TestProperty& test_property);
16149 
16150  // Adds a failure if the key is a reserved attribute of Google Test
16151  // testcase tags. Returns true if the property is valid.
16152  // TODO(russr): Validate attribute names are legal and human readable.
16153  static bool ValidateTestProperty(const TestProperty& test_property);
16154 
16155  // Adds a test part result to the list.
16156  void AddTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& test_part_result);
16157 
16158  // Returns the death test count.
16159  int death_test_count() const { return death_test_count_; }
16160

16162  int increment_death_test_count() { return ++death_test_count_; }
16163 
16164  // Clears the test part results.
16165  void ClearTestPartResults();
16166 
16167  // Clears the object.
16168  void Clear();
16169 
16170  // Protects mutable state of the property vector and of owned
16171  // properties, whose values may be updated.
16172  internal::Mutex test_properites_mutex_;
16173 
16174  // The vector of TestPartResults
16175  std::vector<TestPartResult> test_part_results_;
16176  // The vector of TestProperties
16177  std::vector<TestProperty> test_properties_;
16178  // Running count of death tests.
16179  int death_test_count_;
16180  // The elapsed time, in milliseconds.
16181  TimeInMillis elapsed_time_;
16182 
16183  // We disallow copying TestResult.
16184  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(TestResult);
16185 }; // class TestResult

16187 // A TestInfo object stores the following information about a test:
16188 //
16189 // Test case name
16190 // Test name
16191 // Whether the test should be run
16192 // A function pointer that creates the test object when invoked
16193 // Test result
16194 //
16195 // The constructor of TestInfo registers itself with the UnitTest
16196 // singleton such that the RUN_ALL_TESTS() macro knows which tests to
16197 // run.
16198 class GTEST_API_ TestInfo {
16199  public:
16200  // Destructs a TestInfo object. This function is not virtual, so
16201  // don't inherit from TestInfo.
16202  ~TestInfo();
16203 
16204  // Returns the test case name.
16205  const char* test_case_name() const;
16206 
16207  // Returns the test name.
16208  const char* name() const;
16209 
16210  // Returns the test case comment.
16211  const char* test_case_comment() const;
16212 
16213  // Returns the test comment.
16214  const char* comment() const;
16215 
16216  // Returns true if this test should run, that is if the test is not disabled
16217  // (or it is disabled but the also_run_disabled_tests flag has been specified)
16218  // and its full name matches the user-specified filter.
16219  //
16220  // Google Test allows the user to filter the tests by their full names.
16221  // The full name of a test Bar in test case Foo is defined as
16222  // "Foo.Bar". Only the tests that match the filter will run.
16223  //
16224  // A filter is a colon-separated list of glob (not regex) patterns,
16225  // optionally followed by a '-' and a colon-separated list of
16226  // negative patterns (tests to exclude). A test is run if it
16227  // matches one of the positive patterns and does not match any of
16228  // the negative patterns.
16229  //
16230  // For example, *A*:Foo.* is a filter that matches any string that
16231  // contains the character 'A' or starts with "Foo.".
16232  bool should_run() const;
16233 
16234  // Returns the result of the test.
16235  const TestResult* result() const;
16236 
16237  private:
16238 #if GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
16239  friend class internal::DefaultDeathTestFactory;
16240 #endif // GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
16241  friend class Test;
16242  friend class TestCase;
16243  friend class internal::TestInfoImpl;
16244  friend class internal::UnitTestImpl;
16245  friend TestInfo* internal::MakeAndRegisterTestInfo(
16246  const char* test_case_name, const char* name,
16247  const char* test_case_comment, const char* comment,
16248  internal::TypeId fixture_class_id,
16249  Test::SetUpTestCaseFunc set_up_tc,
16250  Test::TearDownTestCaseFunc tear_down_tc,
16251  internal::TestFactoryBase* factory);
16252 
16253  // Returns true if this test matches the user-specified filter.
16254  bool matches_filter() const;
16255 
16256  // Increments the number of death tests encountered in this test so
16257  // far.
16258  int increment_death_test_count();
16259 
16260  // Accessors for the implementation object.
16261  internal::TestInfoImpl* impl() { return impl_; }
16262  const internal::TestInfoImpl* impl() const { return impl_; }
16263 
16264  // Constructs a TestInfo object. The newly constructed instance assumes
16265  // ownership of the factory object.
16266  TestInfo(const char* test_case_name, const char* name,
16267  const char* test_case_comment, const char* comment,
16268  internal::TypeId fixture_class_id,
16269  internal::TestFactoryBase* factory);
16270 
16271  // An opaque implementation object.
16272  internal::TestInfoImpl* impl_;
16273 
16274  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(TestInfo);
16275 };

16277 // A test case, which consists of a vector of TestInfos.
16278 //
16279 // TestCase is not copyable.
16280 class GTEST_API_ TestCase {

16412 // An Environment object is capable of setting up and tearing down an
16413 // environment. The user should subclass this to define his own
16414 // environment(s).
16415 //
16416 // An Environment object does the set-up and tear-down in virtual
16417 // methods SetUp() and TearDown() instead of the constructor and the
16418 // destructor, as:
16419 //
16420 // 1. You cannot safely throw from a destructor. This is a problem
16421 // as in some cases Google Test is used where exceptions are enabled, and
16422 // we may want to implement ASSERT_* using exceptions where they are
16423 // available.
16424 // 2. You cannot use ASSERT_* directly in a constructor or
16425 // destructor.
16426 class Environment {
16427  public:
16428  // The d'tor is virtual as we need to subclass Environment.
16429  virtual ~Environment() {}
16430 
16431  // Override this to define how to set up the environment.
16432  virtual void SetUp() {}
16433 
16434  // Override this to define how to tear down the environment.
16435  virtual void TearDown() {}
16436  private:
16437  // If you see an error about overriding the following function or
16438  // about it being private, you have mis-spelled SetUp() as Setup().
16439  struct Setup_should_be_spelled_SetUp {};
16440  virtual Setup_should_be_spelled_SetUp* Setup() { return NULL; }
16441 };

16443 // The interface for tracing execution of tests. The methods are organized in
16444 // the order the corresponding events are fired.
16445 class TestEventListener {
16446  public:
16447  virtual ~TestEventListener() {}
16448 
16449  // Fired before any test activity starts.
16450  virtual void OnTestProgramStart(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
16451 
16452  // Fired before each iteration of tests starts. There may be more than
16453  // one iteration if GTEST_FLAG(repeat) is set. iteration is the iteration
16454  // index, starting from 0.
16455  virtual void OnTestIterationStart(const UnitTest& unit_test,
16456  int iteration) = 0;
16457 
16458  // Fired before environment set-up for each iteration of tests starts.
16459  virtual void OnEnvironmentsSetUpStart(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
16460 
16461  // Fired after environment set-up for each iteration of tests ends.
16462  virtual void OnEnvironmentsSetUpEnd(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
16463 
16464  // Fired before the test case starts.
16465  virtual void OnTestCaseStart(const TestCase& test_case) = 0;
16466 
16467  // Fired before the test starts.
16468  virtual void OnTestStart(const TestInfo& test_info) = 0;
16469 
16470  // Fired after a failed assertion or a SUCCESS().
16471  virtual void OnTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& test_part_result) = 0;
16472 
16473  // Fired after the test ends.
16474  virtual void OnTestEnd(const TestInfo& test_info) = 0;
16475 
16476  // Fired after the test case ends.
16477  virtual void OnTestCaseEnd(const TestCase& test_case) = 0;
16478 
16479  // Fired before environment tear-down for each iteration of tests starts.
16480  virtual void OnEnvironmentsTearDownStart(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
16481 
16482  // Fired after environment tear-down for each iteration of tests ends.
16483  virtual void OnEnvironmentsTearDownEnd(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
16484 
16485  // Fired after each iteration of tests finishes.
16486  virtual void OnTestIterationEnd(const UnitTest& unit_test,
16487  int iteration) = 0;
16488 
16489  // Fired after all test activities have ended.
16490  virtual void OnTestProgramEnd(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
16491 };
16492

16494 // methods and are not concerned that a possible change to a signature of

16507  virtual void OnTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& /*test_part_result*/) {}

16510  virtual void OnEnvironmentsTearDownStart(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/) {}

16761 // A convenient wrapper for adding an environment for the test
16762 // program.
16763 //
16764 // You should call this before RUN_ALL_TESTS() is called, probably in
16765 // main(). If you use gtest_main, you need to call this before main()
16766 // starts for it to take effect. For example, you can define a global
16767 // variable like this:
16768 //
16769 // testing::Environment* const foo_env =
16770 // testing::AddGlobalTestEnvironment(new FooEnvironment);
16771 //
16772 // However, we strongly recommend you to write your own main() and
16773 // call AddGlobalTestEnvironment() there, as relying on initialization
16774 // of global variables makes the code harder to read and may cause
16775 // problems when you register multiple environments from different
16776 // translation units and the environments have dependencies among them
16777 // (remember that the compiler doesn't guarantee the order in which
16778 // global variables from different translation units are initialized).
16779 inline Environment* AddGlobalTestEnvironment(Environment* env) {
16780  return UnitTest::GetInstance()->AddEnvironment(env);
16781 }
16782 
16783 // Initializes Google Test. This must be called before calling
16784 // RUN_ALL_TESTS(). In particular, it parses a command line for the
16785 // flags that Google Test recognizes. Whenever a Google Test flag is
16786 // seen, it is removed from argv, and *argc is decremented.
16787 //
16788 // No value is returned. Instead, the Google Test flag variables are
16789 // updated.
16790 //
16791 // Calling the function for the second time has no user-visible effect.
16792 GTEST_API_ void InitGoogleTest(int* argc, char** argv);

16795 // UNICODE mode.

16800 // These overloaded versions handle ::std::string and ::std::wstring.

16802  return (Message() << '"' << str << '"').GetString();
16803 }

16815 }
16816 #endif // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING

16820  return (Message() << "L\"" << wstr << '"').GetString();
