16824 // Formats a comparison assertion (e.g. ASSERT_EQ, EXPECT_LT, and etc)
16825 // operand to be used in a failure message. The type (but not value)
16826 // of the other operand may affect the format. This allows us to
16827 // print a char* as a raw pointer when it is compared against another
16828 // char*, and print it as a C string when it is compared against an
16829 // std::string object, for example.
16830 //
16831 // The default implementation ignores the type of the other operand.
16832 // Some specialized versions are used to handle formatting wide or
16833 // narrow C strings.
16834 //
16835 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
16836 template <typename T1, typename T2>
16837 String FormatForComparisonFailureMessage(const T1& value,
16838  const T2& /* other_operand */) {
16839  return FormatForFailureMessage(value);
16840 }
16841 
16842 // The helper function for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ.
16843 template <typename T1, typename T2>
16844 AssertionResult CmpHelperEQ(const char* expected_expression,
16845  const char* actual_expression,
16846  const T1& expected,
16847  const T2& actual) {
16848 #ifdef _MSC_VER
16849 #pragma warning(push) // Saves the current warning state.
16850 #pragma warning(disable:4389) // Temporarily disables warning on
16851  // signed/unsigned mismatch.
16852 #endif
16853 
16854  if (expected == actual) {
16855  return AssertionSuccess();
16856  }
16857 
16858 #ifdef _MSC_VER
16859 #pragma warning(pop) // Restores the warning state.
16860 #endif
16861 
16862  return EqFailure(expected_expression,
16863  actual_expression,
16864  FormatForComparisonFailureMessage(expected, actual),
16865  FormatForComparisonFailureMessage(actual, expected),
16866  false);
16867 }
16868 
16869 // With this overloaded version, we allow anonymous enums to be used
16870 // in {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ when compiled with gcc 4, as anonymous enums
16871 // can be implicitly cast to BiggestInt.
16872 GTEST_API_ AssertionResult CmpHelperEQ(const char* expected_expression,
16873  const char* actual_expression,
16874  BiggestInt expected,
16875  BiggestInt actual);
16876 
16877 // The helper class for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ. The template argument
16878 // lhs_is_null_literal is true iff the first argument to ASSERT_EQ()
16879 // is a null pointer literal. The following default implementation is
16880 // for lhs_is_null_literal being false.
16881 template <bool lhs_is_null_literal>
16882 class EqHelper {
16883  public:
16884  // This templatized version is for the general case.
16885  template <typename T1, typename T2>
16886  static AssertionResult Compare(const char* expected_expression,
16887  const char* actual_expression,
16888  const T1& expected,
16889  const T2& actual) {
16890  return CmpHelperEQ(expected_expression, actual_expression, expected,
16891  actual);
16892  }
16893 
16894  // With this overloaded version, we allow anonymous enums to be used
16895  // in {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ when compiled with gcc 4, as anonymous
16896  // enums can be implicitly cast to BiggestInt.
16897  //
16898  // Even though its body looks the same as the above version, we
16899  // cannot merge the two, as it will make anonymous enums unhappy.
16900  static AssertionResult Compare(const char* expected_expression,
16901  const char* actual_expression,
16902  BiggestInt expected,
16903  BiggestInt actual) {
16904  return CmpHelperEQ(expected_expression, actual_expression, expected,
16905  actual);
16906  }
16907 };
16908 
16909 // This specialization is used when the first argument to ASSERT_EQ()
16910 // is a null pointer literal.
16911 template <>
16912 class EqHelper<true> {
16913  public:
16914  // We define two overloaded versions of Compare(). The first
16915  // version will be picked when the second argument to ASSERT_EQ() is
16916  // NOT a pointer, e.g. ASSERT_EQ(0, AnIntFunction()) or
16917  // EXPECT_EQ(false, a_bool).
16918  template <typename T1, typename T2>
16919  static AssertionResult Compare(const char* expected_expression,
16920  const char* actual_expression,
16921  const T1& expected,
16922  const T2& actual) {
16923  return CmpHelperEQ(expected_expression, actual_expression, expected,
16924  actual);
16925  }
16926 
16927  // This version will be picked when the second argument to
16928  // ASSERT_EQ() is a pointer, e.g. ASSERT_EQ(NULL, a_pointer).
16929  template <typename T1, typename T2>
16930  static AssertionResult Compare(const char* expected_expression,
16931  const char* actual_expression,
16932  const T1& /* expected */,
16933  T2* actual) {
16934  // We already know that 'expected' is a null pointer.
16935  return CmpHelperEQ(expected_expression, actual_expression,
16936  static_cast<T2*>(NULL), actual);
16937  }
16938 };

16940 // A macro for implementing the helper functions needed to implement
16941 // ASSERT_?? and EXPECT_??. It is here just to avoid copy-and-paste
16942 // of similar code.
16943 //
16944 // For each templatized helper function, we also define an overloaded
16945 // version for BiggestInt in order to reduce code bloat and allow
16946 // anonymous enums to be used with {ASSERT|EXPECT}_?? when compiled
16947 // with gcc 4.
16948 //
16949 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
16950 #define GTEST_IMPL_CMP_HELPER_(op_name, op)\
16951 template <typename T1, typename T2>\
16952 AssertionResult CmpHelper##op_name(const char* expr1, const char* expr2, \
16953  const T1& val1, const T2& val2) {\
16954  if (val1 op val2) {\
16955  return AssertionSuccess();\
16956  } else {\
16957  Message msg;\
16958  msg << "Expected: (" << expr1 << ") " #op " (" << expr2\
16959  << "), actual: " << FormatForComparisonFailureMessage(val1, val2)\
16960  << " vs " << FormatForComparisonFailureMessage(val2, val1);\
16961  return AssertionFailure(msg);\
16962  }\
16963 }\
16964 GTEST_API_ AssertionResult CmpHelper##op_name(\
16965  const char* expr1, const char* expr2, BiggestInt val1, BiggestInt val2)

17071 // Helper template function for comparing floating-points.
17072 //
17073 // Template parameter:
17074 //
17075 // RawType: the raw floating-point type (either float or double)
17076 //
17077 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
17078 template <typename RawType>
17079 AssertionResult CmpHelperFloatingPointEQ(const char* expected_expression,
17080  const char* actual_expression,
17081  RawType expected,
17082  RawType actual) {
17083  const FloatingPoint<RawType> lhs(expected), rhs(actual);
17084 
17085  if (lhs.AlmostEquals(rhs)) {
17086  return AssertionSuccess();
17087  }
17088 
17089  StrStream expected_ss;
17090  expected_ss << std::setprecision(std::numeric_limits<RawType>::digits10 + 2)
17091  << expected;
17092 
17093  StrStream actual_ss;
17094  actual_ss << std::setprecision(std::numeric_limits<RawType>::digits10 + 2)
17095  << actual;
17096 
17097  return EqFailure(expected_expression,
17098  actual_expression,
17099  StrStreamToString(&expected_ss),
17100  StrStreamToString(&actual_ss),
17101  false);
17102 }

17114 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
17115 // A class that enables one to stream messages to assertion macros
17116 class GTEST_API_ AssertHelper {
17117  public:
17118  // Constructor.
17119  AssertHelper(TestPartResult::Type type,
17120  const char* file,
17121  int line,
17122  const char* message);
17123  ~AssertHelper();
17124 
17125  // Message assignment is a semantic trick to enable assertion
17126  // streaming; see the GTEST_MESSAGE_ macro below.
17127  void operator=(const Message& message) const;
17128 
17129  private:
17130  // We put our data in a struct so that the size of the AssertHelper class can
17131  // be as small as possible. This is important because gcc is incapable of
17132  // re-using stack space even for temporary variables, so every EXPECT_EQ
17133  // reserves stack space for another AssertHelper.
17134  struct AssertHelperData {
17135  AssertHelperData(TestPartResult::Type t,
17136  const char* srcfile,
17137  int line_num,
17138  const char* msg)
17139  : type(t), file(srcfile), line(line_num), message(msg) { }
17140 
17141  TestPartResult::Type const type;
17142  const char* const file;
17143  int const line;
17144  String const message;
17145 
17146  private:
17147  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(AssertHelperData);
17148  };
17149 
17150  AssertHelperData* const data_;
17151 
17152  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(AssertHelper);
17153 };

17157 #if GTEST_HAS_PARAM_TEST
17158 // The abstract base class that all value-parameterized tests inherit from.
17159 //
17160 // This class adds support for accessing the test parameter value via
17161 // the GetParam() method.
17162 //
17163 // Use it with one of the parameter generator defining functions, like Range(),
17164 // Values(), ValuesIn(), Bool(), and Combine().
17165 //
17166 // class FooTest : public ::testing::TestWithParam<int> {
17167 // protected:
17168 // FooTest() {
17169 // // Can use GetParam() here.
17170 // }
17171 // virtual ~FooTest() {
17172 // // Can use GetParam() here.
17173 // }
17174 // virtual void SetUp() {
17175 // // Can use GetParam() here.
17176 // }
17177 // virtual void TearDown {
17178 // // Can use GetParam() here.
17179 // }
17180 // };
17181 // TEST_P(FooTest, DoesBar) {
17182 // // Can use GetParam() method here.
17183 // Foo foo;
17184 // ASSERT_TRUE(foo.DoesBar(GetParam()));
17185 // }
17186 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(OneToTenRange, FooTest, ::testing::Range(1, 10));
17187 
17188 template <typename T>
17189 class TestWithParam : public Test {
17190  public:
17191  typedef T ParamType;
17192 
17193  // The current parameter value. Is also available in the test fixture's
17194  // constructor.
17195  const ParamType& GetParam() const { return *parameter_; }
17196 
17197  private:
17198  // Sets parameter value. The caller is responsible for making sure the value
17199  // remains alive and unchanged throughout the current test.
17200  static void SetParam(const ParamType* parameter) {
17201  parameter_ = parameter;
17202  }
17203 
17204  // Static value used for accessing parameter during a test lifetime.
17205  static const ParamType* parameter_;
17206 
17207  // TestClass must be a subclass of TestWithParam<T>.
17208  template <class TestClass> friend class internal::ParameterizedTestFactory;
17209 };
17210 
17211 template <typename T>
17212 const T* TestWithParam<T>::parameter_ = NULL;

17216 // Macros for indicating success/failure in test code.
17217 
17218 // ADD_FAILURE unconditionally adds a failure to the current test.
17219 // SUCCEED generates a success - it doesn't automatically make the
17220 // current test successful, as a test is only successful when it has
17221 // no failure.
17222 //
17223 // EXPECT_* verifies that a certain condition is satisfied. If not,
17224 // it behaves like ADD_FAILURE. In particular:
17225 //
17226 // EXPECT_TRUE verifies that a Boolean condition is true.
17227 // EXPECT_FALSE verifies that a Boolean condition is false.
17228 //
17229 // FAIL and ASSERT_* are similar to ADD_FAILURE and EXPECT_*, except
17230 // that they will also abort the current function on failure. People
17231 // usually want the fail-fast behavior of FAIL and ASSERT_*, but those
17232 // writing data-driven tests often find themselves using ADD_FAILURE
17233 // and EXPECT_* more.
17234 //
17235 // Examples:
17236 //
17237 // EXPECT_TRUE(server.StatusIsOK());
17238 // ASSERT_FALSE(server.HasPendingRequest(port))
17239 // << "There are still pending requests " << "on port " << port;
17240 
17241 // Generates a nonfatal failure with a generic message.
17242 #define ADD_FAILURE() GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_("Failed")
17243 
17244 // Generates a fatal failure with a generic message.
17245 #define GTEST_FAIL() GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_("Failed")
17246 
17247 // Define this macro to 1 to omit the definition of FAIL(), which is a
17248 // generic name and clashes with some other libraries.
17249 #if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_FAIL
17250 #define FAIL() GTEST_FAIL()
17251 #endif
17252 
17253 // Generates a success with a generic message.
17254 #define GTEST_SUCCEED() GTEST_SUCCESS_("Succeeded")
17255 
17256 // Define this macro to 1 to omit the definition of SUCCEED(), which
17257 // is a generic name and clashes with some other libraries.
17258 #if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_SUCCEED
17259 #define SUCCEED() GTEST_SUCCEED()
17260 #endif
17261 
17262 // Macros for testing exceptions.
17263 //
17264 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_THROW(statement, expected_exception):
17265 // Tests that the statement throws the expected exception.
17266 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NO_THROW(statement):
17267 // Tests that the statement doesn't throw any exception.
17268 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_ANY_THROW(statement):
17269 // Tests that the statement throws an exception.
17270 
17271 #define EXPECT_THROW(statement, expected_exception) \
17272  GTEST_TEST_THROW_(statement, expected_exception, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
17273 #define EXPECT_NO_THROW(statement) \
17274  GTEST_TEST_NO_THROW_(statement, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
17275 #define EXPECT_ANY_THROW(statement) \
17276  GTEST_TEST_ANY_THROW_(statement, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
17277 #define ASSERT_THROW(statement, expected_exception) \
17278  GTEST_TEST_THROW_(statement, expected_exception, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
17279 #define ASSERT_NO_THROW(statement) \
17280  GTEST_TEST_NO_THROW_(statement, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
17281 #define ASSERT_ANY_THROW(statement) \
17282  GTEST_TEST_ANY_THROW_(statement, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
17283 
17284 // Boolean assertions. Condition can be either a Boolean expression or an
17285 // AssertionResult. For more information on how to use AssertionResult with
17286 // these macros see comments on that class.
17287 #define EXPECT_TRUE(condition) \
17288  GTEST_TEST_BOOLEAN_(condition, #condition, false, true, \
17289  GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
17290 #define EXPECT_FALSE(condition) \
17291  GTEST_TEST_BOOLEAN_(!(condition), #condition, true, false, \
17292  GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
17293 #define ASSERT_TRUE(condition) \
17294  GTEST_TEST_BOOLEAN_(condition, #condition, false, true, \
17295  GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
17296 #define ASSERT_FALSE(condition) \
17297  GTEST_TEST_BOOLEAN_(!(condition), #condition, true, false, \
17298  GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)

17344 // This header implements a family of generic predicate assertion
17345 // macros:
17346 //
17347 // ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT1(pred_format, v1)
17348 // ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(pred_format, v1, v2)
17349 // ...
17350 //
17351 // where pred_format is a function or functor that takes n (in the
17352 // case of ASSERT_PRED_FORMATn) values and their source expression
17353 // text, and returns a testing::AssertionResult. See the definition
17354 // of ASSERT_EQ in gtest.h for an example.
17355 //
17356 // If you don't care about formatting, you can use the more
17357 // restrictive version:
17358 //
17359 // ASSERT_PRED1(pred, v1)
17360 // ASSERT_PRED2(pred, v1, v2)
17361 // ...
17362 //
17363 // where pred is an n-ary function or functor that returns bool,
17364 // and the values v1, v2, ..., must support the << operator for
17365 // streaming to std::ostream.
17366 //
17367 // We also define the EXPECT_* variations.
17368 //
17369 // For now we only support predicates whose arity is at most 5.
17370 // Please email googletestframework@googlegroups.com if you need
17371 // support for higher arities.
17372 
17373 // GTEST_ASSERT_ is the basic statement to which all of the assertions
17374 // in this file reduce. Don't use this in your code.
17375 
17376 #define GTEST_ASSERT_(expression, on_failure) \
17377  GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
17378  if (const ::testing::AssertionResult gtest_ar = (expression)) \
17379  ; \
17380  else \
17381  on_failure(gtest_ar.failure_message())
17382

17384 // Helper function for implementing {EXPECT|ASSERT}_PRED1. Don't use
17385 // this in your code.
17386 template <typename Pred,
17387  typename T1>
17388 AssertionResult AssertPred1Helper(const char* pred_text,
17389  const char* e1,
17390  Pred pred,
17391  const T1& v1) {
17392  if (pred(v1)) return AssertionSuccess();
17393 
17394  Message msg;
17395  msg << pred_text << "("
17396  << e1 << ") evaluates to false, where"
17397  << "\n" << e1 << " evaluates to " << v1;
17398  return AssertionFailure(msg);
17399 }

17480  typename T1,
17481  typename T2,
17482  typename T3>

17484  const char* e1,
17485  const char* e2,
17486  const char* e3,
17487  Pred pred,
17488  const T1& v1,
17489  const T2& v2,
17490  const T3& v3) {
17491  if (pred(v1, v2, v3)) return AssertionSuccess();
17492 
17493  Message msg;
17494  msg << pred_text << "("
17495  << e1 << ", "
17496  << e2 << ", "
17497  << e3 << ") evaluates to false, where"
17498  << "\n" << e1 << " evaluates to " << v1
17499  << "\n" << e2 << " evaluates to " << v2
17500  << "\n" << e3 << " evaluates to " << v3;
17501  return AssertionFailure(msg);
17502 }

17670 
17671 // Macros for testing equalities and inequalities.
17672 //
17673 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ(expected, actual): Tests that expected == actual
17674 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NE(v1, v2): Tests that v1 != v2
17675 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_LT(v1, v2): Tests that v1 < v2
17676 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_LE(v1, v2): Tests that v1 <= v2
17677 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_GT(v1, v2): Tests that v1 > v2
17678 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_GE(v1, v2): Tests that v1 >= v2
17679 //
17680 // When they are not, Google Test prints both the tested expressions and
17681 // their actual values. The values must be compatible built-in types,
17682 // or you will get a compiler error. By "compatible" we mean that the
17683 // values can be compared by the respective operator.
17684 //
17685 // Note:
17686 //
17687 // 1. It is possible to make a user-defined type work with
17688 // {ASSERT|EXPECT}_??(), but that requires overloading the
17689 // comparison operators and is thus discouraged by the Google C++
17690 // Usage Guide. Therefore, you are advised to use the
17691 // {ASSERT|EXPECT}_TRUE() macro to assert that two objects are
17692 // equal.
17693 //
17694 // 2. The {ASSERT|EXPECT}_??() macros do pointer comparisons on
17695 // pointers (in particular, C strings). Therefore, if you use it
17696 // with two C strings, you are testing how their locations in memory
17697 // are related, not how their content is related. To compare two C
17698 // strings by content, use {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STR*().
17699 //
17700 // 3. {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ(expected, actual) is preferred to
17701 // {ASSERT|EXPECT}_TRUE(expected == actual), as the former tells you
17702 // what the actual value is when it fails, and similarly for the
17703 // other comparisons.
17704 //
17705 // 4. Do not depend on the order in which {ASSERT|EXPECT}_??()
17706 // evaluate their arguments, which is undefined.
17707 //
17708 // 5. These macros evaluate their arguments exactly once.
17709 //
17710 // Examples:
17711 //
17712 // EXPECT_NE(5, Foo());
17713 // EXPECT_EQ(NULL, a_pointer);
17714 // ASSERT_LT(i, array_size);
17715 // ASSERT_GT(records.size(), 0) << "There is no record left.";
17716 
17717 #define EXPECT_EQ(expected, actual) \
17718  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal:: \
17719  EqHelper<GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(expected)>::Compare, \
17720  expected, actual)
17721 #define EXPECT_NE(expected, actual) \
17722  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperNE, expected, actual)
17723 #define EXPECT_LE(val1, val2) \
17724  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperLE, val1, val2)
17725 #define EXPECT_LT(val1, val2) \
17726  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperLT, val1, val2)
17727 #define EXPECT_GE(val1, val2) \
17728  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperGE, val1, val2)
17729 #define EXPECT_GT(val1, val2) \
17730  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperGT, val1, val2)
17731 
17732 #define ASSERT_EQ(expected, actual) \
17733  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal:: \
17734  EqHelper<GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(expected)>::Compare, \
17735  expected, actual)
17736 #define ASSERT_NE(val1, val2) \
17737  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperNE, val1, val2)
17738 #define ASSERT_LE(val1, val2) \
17739  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperLE, val1, val2)
17740 #define ASSERT_LT(val1, val2) \
17741  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperLT, val1, val2)
17742 #define ASSERT_GE(val1, val2) \
17743  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperGE, val1, val2)
17744 #define ASSERT_GT(val1, val2) \
17745  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperGT, val1, val2)
17746 
17747 // C String Comparisons. All tests treat NULL and any non-NULL string
17748 // as different. Two NULLs are equal.
17749 //
17750 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STREQ(s1, s2): Tests that s1 == s2
17751 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STRNE(s1, s2): Tests that s1 != s2
17752 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STRCASEEQ(s1, s2): Tests that s1 == s2, ignoring case
17753 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STRCASENE(s1, s2): Tests that s1 != s2, ignoring case
17754 //
17755 // For wide or narrow string objects, you can use the
17756 // {ASSERT|EXPECT}_??() macros.
17757 //
17758 // Don't depend on the order in which the arguments are evaluated,
17759 // which is undefined.
17760 //
17761 // These macros evaluate their arguments exactly once.
17762 
17763 #define EXPECT_STREQ(expected, actual) \
17764  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTREQ, expected, actual)
17765 #define EXPECT_STRNE(s1, s2) \
17766  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRNE, s1, s2)
17767 #define EXPECT_STRCASEEQ(expected, actual) \
17768  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRCASEEQ, expected, actual)
17769 #define EXPECT_STRCASENE(s1, s2)\
17770  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRCASENE, s1, s2)
17771 
17772 #define ASSERT_STREQ(expected, actual) \
17773  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTREQ, expected, actual)
17774 #define ASSERT_STRNE(s1, s2) \
17775  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRNE, s1, s2)
17776 #define ASSERT_STRCASEEQ(expected, actual) \
17777  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRCASEEQ, expected, actual)
17778 #define ASSERT_STRCASENE(s1, s2)\
17779  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRCASENE, s1, s2)
17780 
17781 // Macros for comparing floating-point numbers.
17782 //
17783 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_FLOAT_EQ(expected, actual):
17784 // Tests that two float values are almost equal.
17785 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_DOUBLE_EQ(expected, actual):
17786 // Tests that two double values are almost equal.
17787 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NEAR(v1, v2, abs_error):
17788 // Tests that v1 and v2 are within the given distance to each other.
17789 //
17790 // Google Test uses ULP-based comparison to automatically pick a default
17791 // error bound that is appropriate for the operands. See the
17792 // FloatingPoint template class in gtest-internal.h if you are
17793 // interested in the implementation details.
17794 
17795 #define EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(expected, actual)\
17796  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperFloatingPointEQ<float>, \
17797  expected, actual)
17798 
17799 #define EXPECT_DOUBLE_EQ(expected, actual)\
17800  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperFloatingPointEQ<double>, \
17801  expected, actual)
17802 
17803 #define ASSERT_FLOAT_EQ(expected, actual)\
17804  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperFloatingPointEQ<float>, \
17805  expected, actual)
17806 
17807 #define ASSERT_DOUBLE_EQ(expected, actual)\
17808  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperFloatingPointEQ<double>, \
17809  expected, actual)
17810 
17811 #define EXPECT_NEAR(val1, val2, abs_error)\
17812  EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT3(::testing::internal::DoubleNearPredFormat, \
17813  val1, val2, abs_error)
17814 
17815 #define ASSERT_NEAR(val1, val2, abs_error)\
17816  ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT3(::testing::internal::DoubleNearPredFormat, \
17817  val1, val2, abs_error)

17819 // These predicate format functions work on floating-point values, and
17820 // can be used in {ASSERT|EXPECT}_PRED_FORMAT2*(), e.g.
17821 //
17822 // EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(testing::DoubleLE, Foo(), 5.0);

17824 // Asserts that val1 is less than, or almost equal to, val2. Fails
17825 // otherwise. In particular, it fails if either val1 or val2 is NaN.
17826 GTEST_API_ AssertionResult FloatLE(const char* expr1, const char* expr2,
17827  float val1, float val2);
17828 GTEST_API_ AssertionResult DoubleLE(const char* expr1, const char* expr2,
17829  double val1, double val2);

17834 // Macros that test for HRESULT failure and success, these are only useful
17835 // on Windows, and rely on Windows SDK macros and APIs to compile.
17836 //
17837 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_HRESULT_{SUCCEEDED|FAILED}(expr)
17838 //
17839 // When expr unexpectedly fails or succeeds, Google Test prints the

17842 // hex result code.

17857 // Macros that execute statement and check that it doesn't generate new fatal
17858 // failures in the current thread.
17859 //
17860 // * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(statement);
17861 //
17862 // Examples:
17863 //
17864 // EXPECT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(Process());
17865 // ASSERT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(Process()) << "Process() failed";
17866 //
17867 #define ASSERT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(statement) \
17868  GTEST_TEST_NO_FATAL_FAILURE_(statement, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
17869 #define EXPECT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(statement) \
17870  GTEST_TEST_NO_FATAL_FAILURE_(statement, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
17871 
17872 // Causes a trace (including the source file path, the current line
17873 // number, and the given message) to be included in every test failure
17874 // message generated by code in the current scope. The effect is
17875 // undone when the control leaves the current scope.
17876 //
17877 // The message argument can be anything streamable to std::ostream.
17878 //
17879 // In the implementation, we include the current line number as part
17880 // of the dummy variable name, thus allowing multiple SCOPED_TRACE()s
17881 // to appear in the same block - as long as they are on different
17882 // lines.
17883 #define SCOPED_TRACE(message) \
17884  ::testing::internal::ScopedTrace GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_trace_, __LINE__)(\
17885  __FILE__, __LINE__, ::testing::Message() << (message))

17887 namespace internal {
17888 
17889 // This template is declared, but intentionally undefined.
17890 template <typename T1, typename T2>
17891 struct StaticAssertTypeEqHelper;
17892 
17893 template <typename T>
17894 struct StaticAssertTypeEqHelper<T, T> {};
17895 
17896 } // namespace internal
17897 
17898 // Compile-time assertion for type equality.
17899 // StaticAssertTypeEq<type1, type2>() compiles iff type1 and type2 are
17900 // the same type. The value it returns is not interesting.
17901 //
17902 // Instead of making StaticAssertTypeEq a class template, we make it a
17903 // function template that invokes a helper class template. This
17904 // prevents a user from misusing StaticAssertTypeEq<T1, T2> by
17905 // defining objects of that type.
17906 //
17907 // CAVEAT:
17908 //
17909 // When used inside a method of a class template,
17910 // StaticAssertTypeEq<T1, T2>() is effective ONLY IF the method is
17911 // instantiated. For example, given:
17912 //
17913 // template <typename T> class Foo {
17914 // public:
17915 // void Bar() { testing::StaticAssertTypeEq<int, T>(); }
17916 // };
17917 //
17918 // the code:
17919 //
17920 // void Test1() { Foo<bool> foo; }
17921 //
17922 // will NOT generate a compiler error, as Foo<bool>::Bar() is never
17923 // actually instantiated. Instead, you need:
17924 //
17925 // void Test2() { Foo<bool> foo; foo.Bar(); }
17926 //
17927 // to cause a compiler error.
17928 template <typename T1, typename T2>
17929 bool StaticAssertTypeEq() {
17930  internal::StaticAssertTypeEqHelper<T1, T2>();
17931  return true;
17932 }
17933 
17934 // Defines a test.
17935 //
17936 // The first parameter is the name of the test case, and the second
17937 // parameter is the name of the test within the test case.
17938 //
17939 // The convention is to end the test case name with "Test". For
17940 // example, a test case for the Foo class can be named FooTest.
17941 //
17942 // The user should put his test code between braces after using this
17943 // macro. Example:
17944 //
17945 // TEST(FooTest, InitializesCorrectly) {
17946 // Foo foo;
17947 // EXPECT_TRUE(foo.StatusIsOK());
17948 // }
17949 
17950 // Note that we call GetTestTypeId() instead of GetTypeId<
17951 // ::testing::Test>() here to get the type ID of testing::Test. This
17952 // is to work around a suspected linker bug when using Google Test as
17953 // a framework on Mac OS X. The bug causes GetTypeId<
17954 // ::testing::Test>() to return different values depending on whether
17955 // the call is from the Google Test framework itself or from user test
17956 // code. GetTestTypeId() is guaranteed to always return the same
17957 // value, as it always calls GetTypeId<>() from the Google Test
17958 // framework.
17959 #define GTEST_TEST(test_case_name, test_name)\
17960  GTEST_TEST_(test_case_name, test_name, \
17961  ::testing::Test, ::testing::internal::GetTestTypeId())
17962 
17963 // Define this macro to 1 to omit the definition of TEST(), which
17964 // is a generic name and clashes with some other libraries.
17965 #if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_TEST
17966 #define TEST(test_case_name, test_name) GTEST_TEST(test_case_name, test_name)
17967 #endif
17968 
17969 // Defines a test that uses a test fixture.
17970 //
17971 // The first parameter is the name of the test fixture class, which
17972 // also doubles as the test case name. The second parameter is the
17973 // name of the test within the test case.
17974 //
17975 // A test fixture class must be declared earlier. The user should put
17976 // his test code between braces after using this macro. Example:
17977 //
17978 // class FooTest : public testing::Test {
17979 // protected:
17980 // virtual void SetUp() { b_.AddElement(3); }
17981 //
17982 // Foo a_;
17983 // Foo b_;
17984 // };
17985 //
17986 // TEST_F(FooTest, InitializesCorrectly) {
17987 // EXPECT_TRUE(a_.StatusIsOK());
17988 // }
17989 //
17990 // TEST_F(FooTest, ReturnsElementCountCorrectly) {
17991 // EXPECT_EQ(0, a_.size());
17992 // EXPECT_EQ(1, b_.size());
17993 // }
17994 
17995 #define TEST_F(test_fixture, test_name)\
17996  GTEST_TEST_(test_fixture, test_name, test_fixture, \
17997  ::testing::internal::GetTypeId<test_fixture>())
17998 
17999 // Use this macro in main() to run all tests. It returns 0 if all
18000 // tests are successful, or 1 otherwise.
18001 //
18002 // RUN_ALL_TESTS() should be invoked after the command line has been
18003 // parsed by InitGoogleTest().
18004 
18005 #define RUN_ALL_TESTS()\
18006  (::testing::UnitTest::GetInstance()->Run())
18007 
18008 } // namespace testing
18009 
18010 #endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_H_
